{"title_page": "American Center of Oriental Research", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name          = American Center of Oriental Research\n| bgcolor       = <!-- header background color -->\n| fgcolor       = <!-- header text color -->\n| image         = \n| image_border  = \n| size          = 123px\n| alt           = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption       = \n| map           = <!-- optional -->\n| msize         = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt          = <!-- map alt text -->\n| mcaption      = <!-- optional -->\n| map2          = \n| abbreviation  = \n| motto         = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| formation     = 1968\n| extinction    = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n| type          = [[Research Center]]\n| status        = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n| purpose       = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc -->\n| headquarters  = Alexandria, Virginia, USA, and [[Amman]], Jordan\n| location      = \n| coords        = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template -->\n| region_served = \n| membership    = \n| language      = <!-- official languages -->\n| general       = <!-- Secretary General -->\n| leader_title  = Director\n| leader_name   = Pearce Paul Creasman, Ph.D.\n| leader_title2 = President\n| leader_name2  = Edward W. Gnehm, Jr.\n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3  = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4  = \n| key_people    = \n| main_organ    = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| Member_of =\n| affiliations  =  [[Council of American Overseas Research Centers]], [[American Schools of Oriental Research]] \n| budget        = \n| num_staff     = \n| num_volunteers = \n| website       = {{url|http://acorjordan.org/}}\n| remarks       = \n| former name   = \n}}\n\nThe '''American Center of Oriental Research''' ('''ACOR''') is a private, not-for-profit academic institution, research library, and hostel. Based in Alexandria, Virginia, with a facility in Amman, Jordan, ACOR promotes the study of the [[MENA]] region, with an emphasis on the archaeology of Jordan. The institution is a member of the [[American Schools of Oriental Research|American Schools of Oriental Research (ASOR)]] and the [[Council of American Overseas Research Centers|Council of American Overseas Research Centers (CAORC)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/component/content/article/8-main-content/1-welcome-to-our-site|title=:: American Center of Oriental Research ::|author=Super User|work=acorjordan.org|access-date=2015-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402120132/http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/component/content/article/8-main-content/1-welcome-to-our-site|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nACOR's lineage spans back to the foundation of the American School of Oriental Research in 1900, supporting the study of the MENA region. As the region changed during the mid-20th century, the foundation of a permanent research center for [[Americans]] working or studying in the Arab World needed, and in 1968 ACOR itself was created as \"The American Research Center in Amman.\"\n\nIt was first directed by Rudolph H. Dornemann, followed by Murray B. Nicol. It became \"The American Center of Oriental Research\" in 1970.<ref name=\"First\">{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= ACOR: The First 25 Years: The American Center of Oriental Research: 1968-1993 |url= |location= Amman, Jordan |publisher= ACOR |pages= 9\u201383 |date= 1993 |isbn= |access-date= }}</ref> One of ACOR's first projects was excavating a Byzantine church in Swafiyeh, Amman, by the director and annual professor Bastiaan Van Elderen in partnership with Jordan's Department of Antiquities, also serving as a training course for students attending the [[University of Jordan]]. From June 7\u201313, 1970, Van Elderen and various residents barricaded themselves in the ACOR residence during fighting between the [[Palestine Liberation Organization|Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO)]] and the [[Jordanian army]]. Murray Nicol was appointed new director in 1970 but was prevented from serving by the second phase of the war in Jordan, so Siegfried H. Horn replaced him at the urging of the U.S. Embassy in Amman, followed by Henry O. Thompson. In 1975 George Mendenhall was director, followed by James A. Sauer from 1976-1981.\n\nIn 1976 the building was remodeled, adding hostel accommodation for eight people and a 1,800-book library. In 1980 ACOR began partnership with the [[United States Agency for International Development|United States Agency for International Development (USAID)]] and was awarded a contract to write a five-year plan for archaeological development. In 1982 David McCreery became director, and ACOR began to grant fellowships. ACOR moved to a purpose-built building in 1986, with partial funding from USAID's office of [[American Schools and Hospitals Abroad]] and a ribbon-cutting ceremony by H.R.H. Prince Mohammed Bin Talal. In 1988 Bert de Vries took over as director, succeeded by Pierre Bikai in 1991,<ref name=\"First\"/> Barbara A. Porter in 2006, and Pearce Paul Creasman in 2020.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Porter |first= Barbara A. |date= Summer 2008 |title= Barbara Porter's Reflections |url= http://www.acorjordan.org/images/pdf/ACOR%20Newsletter%20Vol.%2020.1.pdf |journal= ACOR Newsletter |location=  |volume= 20.1 |access-date= March 11, 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Several longterm staff included cook Mohammed Adawi, born around in the Palestinian village of Zakariyya, who served as such for the duration of ACOR's existence <ref>{{cite journal |last= Porter |first= Barbara A. |date= Summer 2008 |title= Mohammed Adawi Remembers |url= http://www.acorjordan.org/images/pdf/ACOR%20Newsletter%20Vol.%2020.1.pdf |journal= ACOR Newsletter |location=  |volume= 20.1 |access-date= March 11, 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and Librarian Carmen (Humi) Ayoubi, who managed the library from 1988 to 2020.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Ayoubi |first= Humi |date= Summer 2008 |title= Reflections by Humi Ayoubi |url= http://www.acorjordan.org/images/pdf/ACOR%20Newsletter%20Vol.%2020.1.pdf |journal= ACOR Newsletter |location=  |volume= 20.1 |access-date= March 11, 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAs a member of ASOR, it has a strict policy of non-involvement in politics and follows their code of archaeological ethics.<ref name=\"First\"/>\n\n==Notable ACOR Excavations ==\nACOR has led or been affiliated with many archaeological and restoration projects in the area, most notably: [['Ain Ghazal]], [[Amman Citadel|Amman Citadel's Temple of Hercules]], Ayla in [[Aqaba]], [[Bab edh-Dhra]], [[Hesban]], [[Humeima]], [[Khirbet Iskander]], [[Madaba|Madaba Archaeological Park Project]], [[Pella, Jordan|Pella]], [[Petra|Petra Church]] Project, [[Temple of the Winged Lions|Petra Temple of the Winged Lions Cultural Resource Management]], and [[Umm el-Jimal]].\n\n== ACOR Photo Archive ==\nIn 2016, ACOR began a four-year project to digitize and preserve photographs of Jordan and surrounding areas. Photographs from six different private collections are part of the project donated by [[George Bass (archaeologist)|George Bass]], Linda Jacobs, [[Rami George Khouri|Rami Khouri]],  Robert Schick, Jane Taylor, and Charles Wilson. This project is available online at https://acor.digitalrelab.com/.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/digital-archive-aims-preserve-jordans-past-future-generations|title=Digital archive aims to preserve Jordan\u2019s past for future generations|date=2019-07-01|website=Jordan Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==ACOR Fellowships==\nACOR presents fellowships to students from Jordan, The United States, and other countries. They include: the NEH Fellowship, the ACOR-CAORC Post Graduate Fellowship, the ACOR-CAORC Pre-Doctorate Fellowship, the Jennifer C. Groot Memorial Fellowship, the Bert and Sally de Vries Fellowship, the Harrell Family Fellowship, the Pierre and Patricia Bikai Fellowship, the Burton MacDonald and Rosemarie Sampson Fellowship, the Kenneth W. Russell Fellowship, the James A. Sauer Fellowship, the Frederick-Wenger Memorial Endowment, the Jordanian Graduate Student Scholarship and the Jordanian Travel Scholarship for ASOR Annual Meeting. Scholars can also apply to the CAORC Multi-Country Fellowship Program and the Andrew. W. Mellon Mediterranean Regional Research Fellowship Program.<ref>{{cite web |title=2015-2016 ACOR Fellowships |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/fellow-one |access-date=15 Mar 2015 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150311143822/http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/fellow-one |archive-date=2015-03-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://acorjordan.wordpress.com/2015/02/24/amman-snowstorm/ ACOR Blog]\n* [http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/2013-02-16-12-57-43/acor-newsletters ACOR Newsletters]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140413201708/http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en ACOR Website]\n*[https://acor.digitalrelab.com/index.php ACOR Photo Archive]\n\n{{coord missing|Jordan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Council of American Overseas Research Centers]]\n[[Category:Non-profit academic publishers]]\n[[Category:Research libraries]]\n[[Category:Hostels]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Jordan]]\n", "text_old": "{{primary sources|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name          = American Center of Oriental Research\n| bgcolor       = <!-- header background color -->\n| fgcolor       = <!-- header text color -->\n| image         = \n| image_border  = \n| size          = 123px\n| alt           = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption       = \n| map           = <!-- optional -->\n| msize         = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt          = <!-- map alt text -->\n| mcaption      = <!-- optional -->\n| map2          = \n| abbreviation  = \n| motto         = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| formation     = 1968\n| extinction    = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n| type          = [[Research Center]]\n| status        = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n| purpose       = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc -->\n| headquarters  = Alexandria, Virginia, USA, and [[Amman]], Jordan\n| location      = \n| coords        = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template -->\n| region_served = \n| membership    = \n| language      = <!-- official languages -->\n| general       = <!-- Secretary General -->\n| leader_title  = Director\n| leader_name   = Pearce Paul Creasman, Ph.D.\n| leader_title2 = President\n| leader_name2  = Edward W. Gnehm, Jr.\n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3  = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4  = \n| key_people    = \n| main_organ    = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| Member_of =\n| affiliations  =  [[Council of American Overseas Research Centers]], [[American Schools of Oriental Research]] \n| budget        = \n| num_staff     = \n| num_volunteers = \n| website       = {{url|http://acorjordan.org/}}\n| remarks       = \n| former name   = \n}}\n\nThe '''American Center of Oriental Research''' ('''ACOR''') is a private, not-for-profit academic institution, research library, and hostel. Based in Alexandria, Virginia, with a facility in Amman, Jordan, ACOR promotes the study of the [[MENA]] region, with an emphasis on the archaeology of Jordan. The institution is a member of the [[American Schools of Oriental Research|American Schools of Oriental Research (ASOR)]] and the [[Council of American Overseas Research Centers|Council of American Overseas Research Centers (CAORC)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/component/content/article/8-main-content/1-welcome-to-our-site|title=:: American Center of Oriental Research ::|author=Super User|work=acorjordan.org|access-date=2015-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402120132/http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/component/content/article/8-main-content/1-welcome-to-our-site|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nACOR's lineage spans back to the foundation of the American School of Oriental Research in 1900, supporting the study of the MENA region. As the region changed during the mid-20th century, the foundation of a permanent research center for [[Americans]] working or studying in the Arab World needed, and in 1968 ACOR itself was created as \"The American Research Center in Amman.\"\n\nIt was first directed by Rudolph H. Dornemann, followed by Murray B. Nicol. It became \"The American Center of Oriental Research\" in 1970.<ref name=\"First\">{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= ACOR: The First 25 Years: The American Center of Oriental Research: 1968-1993 |url= |location= Amman, Jordan |publisher= ACOR |pages= 9\u201383 |date= 1993 |isbn= |access-date= }}</ref> One of ACOR's first projects was excavating a Byzantine church in Swafiyeh, Amman, by the director and annual professor Bastiaan Van Elderen in partnership with Jordan's Department of Antiquities, also serving as a training course for students attending the [[University of Jordan]]. From June 7\u201313, 1970, Van Elderen and various residents barricaded themselves in the ACOR residence during fighting between the [[Palestine Liberation Organization|Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO)]] and the [[Jordanian army]]. Murray Nicol was appointed new director in 1970 but was prevented from serving by the second phase of the war in Jordan, so Siegfried H. Horn replaced him at the urging of the U.S. Embassy in Amman, followed by Henry O. Thompson. In 1975 George Mendenhall was director, followed by James A. Sauer from 1976-1981. \n\nIn 1976 the building was remodeled, adding hostel accommodation for eight people and a 1,800-book library. In 1980 ACOR began partnership with the [[United States Agency for International Development|United States Agency for International Development (USAID)]] and was awarded a contract to write a five-year plan for archaeological development. In 1982 David McCreery became director, and ACOR began to grant fellowships. ACOR moved to a purpose-built building in 1986, with partial funding from USAID's office of [[American Schools and Hospitals Abroad]] and a ribbon-cutting ceremony by H.R.H. Prince Mohammed Bin Talal. In 1988 Bert de Vries took over as director, succeeded by Pierre Bikai in 1991 <ref name=\"First\"/>, Barbara A. Porter in 2006, and Pearce Paul Creasman in 2020.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Porter |first= Barbara A. |date= Summer 2008 |title= Barbara Porter's Reflections |url= http://www.acorjordan.org/images/pdf/ACOR%20Newsletter%20Vol.%2020.1.pdf |journal= ACOR Newsletter |location=  |volume= 20.1 |access-date= March 11, 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Several longterm staff included cook Mohammed Adawi, born around in the Palestinian village of Zakariyya, who served as such for the duration of ACOR's existence <ref>{{cite journal |last= Porter |first= Barbara A. |date= Summer 2008 |title= Mohammed Adawi Remembers |url= http://www.acorjordan.org/images/pdf/ACOR%20Newsletter%20Vol.%2020.1.pdf |journal= ACOR Newsletter |location=  |volume= 20.1 |access-date= March 11, 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and Librarian Carmen (Humi) Ayoubi, who managed the library from 1988 to 2020.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Ayoubi |first= Humi |date= Summer 2008 |title= Reflections by Humi Ayoubi |url= http://www.acorjordan.org/images/pdf/ACOR%20Newsletter%20Vol.%2020.1.pdf |journal= ACOR Newsletter |location=  |volume= 20.1 |access-date= March 11, 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAs a member of ASOR, it has a strict policy of non-involvement in politics and follows their code of archaeological ethics.<ref name=\"First\"/>\n\n==Notable ACOR Excavations ==\nACOR has led or been affiliated with many archaeological and restoration projects in the area, most notably: [['Ain Ghazal]], [[Amman Citadel|Amman Citadel's Temple of Hercules]], Ayla in [[Aqaba]], [[Bab edh-Dhra]], [[Hesban]], [[Humeima]], [[Khirbet Iskander]], [[Madaba|Madaba Archaeological Park Project]], [[Pella, Jordan|Pella]], [[Petra|Petra Church]] Project, [[Temple of the Winged Lions|Petra Temple of the Winged Lions Cultural Resource Management]], and [[Umm el-Jimal]].\n\n== ACOR Photo Archive ==\nIn 2016, ACOR began a four-year project to digitize and preserve photographs of Jordan and surrounding areas. Photographs from six different private collections are part of the project donated by [[George Bass (archaeologist)|George Bass]], Linda Jacobs, [[Rami George Khouri|Rami Khouri]],  Robert Schick, Jane Taylor, and Charles Wilson. This project is available online at https://acor.digitalrelab.com/.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/digital-archive-aims-preserve-jordans-past-future-generations|title=Digital archive aims to preserve Jordan\u2019s past for future generations|date=2019-07-01|website=Jordan Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==ACOR Fellowships==\nACOR presents fellowships to students from Jordan, The United States, and other countries. They include: the NEH Fellowship, the ACOR-CAORC Post Graduate Fellowship, the ACOR-CAORC Pre-Doctorate Fellowship, the Jennifer C. Groot Memorial Fellowship, the Bert and Sally de Vries Fellowship, the Harrell Family Fellowship, the Pierre and Patricia Bikai Fellowship, the Burton MacDonald and Rosemarie Sampson Fellowship, the Kenneth W. Russell Fellowship, the James A. Sauer Fellowship, the Frederick-Wenger Memorial Endowment, the Jordanian Graduate Student Scholarship and the Jordanian Travel Scholarship for ASOR Annual Meeting. Scholars can also apply to the CAORC Multi-Country Fellowship Program and the Andrew. W. Mellon Mediterranean Regional Research Fellowship Program.<ref>{{cite web |title=2015-2016 ACOR Fellowships |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/fellow-one |access-date=15 Mar 2015 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150311143822/http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/fellow-one |archive-date=2015-03-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://acorjordan.wordpress.com/2015/02/24/amman-snowstorm/ ACOR Blog]\n* [http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en/2013-02-16-12-57-43/acor-newsletters ACOR Newsletters]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140413201708/http://acorjordan.org/index.php/en ACOR Website]\n*[https://acor.digitalrelab.com/index.php ACOR Photo Archive]\n\n{{coord missing|Jordan}}\n\n[[Category:Council of American Overseas Research Centers]]\n[[Category:Non-profit academic publishers]]\n[[Category:Research libraries]]\n[[Category:Hostels]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Jordan]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Center_of_Oriental_Research"}
{"title_page": "The Last Kids on Earth (TV series)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = The Last Kids On Earth \n| image             = File:The Last Kids on Earth.jpg\n| caption           = Promotional poster\n| genre             = <!-- Must be reliably sourced -->\n| creator           =\n| based_on          = {{based_on|[[The Last Kids on Earth]]||[[Max Brallier]]}}\n| writer            = \n| director          = {{Plainlist|\n* William Lau {{small|(book 1)}}\n* Steve Rolston {{small|(book 2)}}\n}}\n| story             = \n| starring          = Nick Wolfhard\n| composer          = Marcelo Trevino\n| country           = United States <br> Canada\n| language          = English \n| num_seasons       = 2\n| num_episodes      = 11\n| list_episodes     = #Episodes\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Max Brallier\n* Scott Peterson\n* Jennifer McCarron\n* [[Matthew Berkowitz]]\n}}\n| producer = \n| location =\n| cinematography =\n| editor = \n| camera =\n| runtime = 60 minutes (book 1)<br>23 minutes (book 2)\n| picture_format = [[HDTV]] [[1080p]]\n| audio_format = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| company = [[Atomic Cartoons]]\n| distributor =\n| network = [[Netflix]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2019|09|17}}\n| last_aired = present\n| website = https://www.netflix.com/title/80219119\n| website_title = Official website\n}}\n\n'''''The Last Kids on Earth''''' is an American-Canadian [[children's television series|children's]] [[Animated series|animation]] [[web television]] series, based on the [[The Last Kids on Earth|book series of the same name]] by [[Max Brallier]], that premiered on [[Netflix]] on September 17, 2019. A ten-episode second season, or \"Book 2\", titled ''The Last Kids on Earth and the Zombie Parade'', premiered on April 17, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/netflix-trailers-the-last-kids-on-earth-season-2/|title=Netflix Trailers 'The Last Kids on Earth' Season 2|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|date=April 3, 2020|work=[[Animation Magazine]]|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of book two's tenth episode, it was announced that the series will return for a third book / season.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n* Nick Wolfhard as Jack Sullivan, a 13-year-old orphan and video gamer turned hero thanks to the apocalypse.\n* [[Charles Demers]] as Dirk Savage, a former school bully turned strongman and monster fighter on Jack's team. He likes cooking and gardening. \n* Montserrat Hernandez as June Del Toro, a tomboyish 13-year-old girl who is Jack's crush but did not reciprocate his feelings, but starts to develop some in book 2. She was trying to survive on her own until her parents come back for her with a rescue party; but she joins Jack's team and learns to have fun during the apocalypse. She was editor in chief of the school's paper.\n* Garland Whitt as Quint Baker, Jack's nerdy best friend who invents most of the gadgets the kids use to survive in their post-apocalyptic environment.\n* [[Brian Drummond]] as the vocal effects for Rover, a blue-furred canine-like monster who befriends Jack in Book 1 and becomes the team's pet and mascot.\n* [[Mark Hamill]] as Bardle, a gruff monster conjurer that takes up residence in Joe's Pizza<ref name=oller>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/mark-hamill-rosario-dawson-last-kids-on-earth-reveal|title=First Look: Mark Hamill and Rosario Dawson Have a Monster Good Time in The Last Kids on Earth|last=Oller|first=Jacob|date=April 15, 2020|website=Syfy Wire|publisher=[[Syfy]]|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Catherine O'Hara]] as Skaelka, a female monster warrior that takes up residence in Joe's Pizza and becomes a friend of June's<ref name=trumbore>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/last-kids-on-earth-netflix-season-2-cast-images-bruce-campbell-catherine-ohara/|title=Exclusive: 'The Last Kids on Earth' Season 2 Characters Revealed in First-Look Images|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|date=April 13, 2020|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Keith David]] as Thrull, the main antagonist of book two. \n* [[Bruce Campbell]] as Chef, a cranky monster that takes up residence in Joe's Pizza<ref name=trumbore /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/tv/3612967/heres-new-monster-voiced-bruce-campbell-netflixs-last-kids-earth-image/|title=Here's the New Monster Being Voiced by Bruce Campbell in Netflix's \"The Last Kids on Earth\" [Image]|last=Squires|first=John|date=April 14, 2020|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Rosario Dawson]] as Rezzoch<ref name=oller />, the main antagonist of the series as revealed in the Book 2 finale episode.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#000000 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web |title=The Last Kids on Earth \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/last-kids-on-earth/listings/ |website=The Futon Critic |accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> |released=y |country=US |episodes=\n{{Episode table/part|p=Book 1|c=#000|nopart=y}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = The Last Kids on Earth\n |DirectedBy      = Will Lau\n |WrittenBy       = Max Brallier & Scott Peterson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = Living solo in his recently-monster-infested town, 13-year-old Jack will have to think fast, find friends and get creative if he wants to survive.\n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode table/part|p=Book 2|c=#000|nopart=y}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = Mall Quest\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Max Brallier\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = Jack the Slayer\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Jennifer Muro\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = Bestiary Master\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Scott Peterson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = The Zombie Parade\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Haley Mancini\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = The Thrull of Victory\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Joshua Pruett\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = Stay on Target\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Joshua Pruett\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = June Gloom\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Haley Mancini\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = Follow That Butler\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Max Brallier\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = Always Darkest\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Scott Peterson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = Dawn of Rezzoch\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Jennifer Muro\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\nOn September 26, 2017, it was announced that [[Thunderbird Entertainment]]'s animation studio [[Atomic Cartoons]] had optioned the screen rights on Max Brallier's book series ''The Last Kids on Earth'' with the intention of producing an animated television series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McLean|first1=Tom|title=Atomic Brings 'The Last Kids on Earth' To TV|url=https://www.awn.com/news/atomic-brings-last-kids-earth-tv|website=Animation World Network|accessdate=February 28, 2018|language=en|date=September 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Whyte|first=Alexandra|title=Atomic Cartoons options The Last Kids on Earth|url=http://kidscreen.com/2017/09/26/atomic-cartoons-options-the-last-kids-on-earth/|website=Kidscreen|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=September 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 26, 2018, it was announced that Netflix had given the production a series order. Executive producers include Brallier, Scott Peterson, Jennifer McCarron, and [[Matthew Berkowitz]]. Brallier and Peterson are also expected to write the series as well. Production companies involved in the series include [[Thunderbird Entertainment]]'s animation studio [[Atomic Cartoons]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title='The Last Kids On Earth' Animated Comedy Series Based On Books Ordered By Netflix|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/the-last-kids-on-earth-animated-comedy-series-based-books-netflix-1202305024/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=February 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Netflix Orders Animated Series 'The Last Kids on Earth'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/netflix-orders-animated-series-last-kids-earth-1089632|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 28, 2018|language=en|date=February 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2019, the series cast was announced, including [[Mark Hamill]], [[Rosario Dawson]], [[Catherine O'Hara]], [[Keith David]], [[Bruce Campbell]], Garland Whitt, Montserrat Hernandez, Charles Demers, and Nick Wolfhard as the lead character Jack Sullivan.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|title=\u2018The Last Kids On Earth\u2019: Mark Hamill, Rosario Dawson, Catherine O\u2019Hara and Others Set For Netflix Animated Series|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-last-kids-on-earth-netflix-mark-hamill-rosario-dawson-catherine-ohara-keith-david-bruce-campbell-garland-whitt-montse-hernandez-charles-demers-nick-wolfhard-1202574577|website=Deadline|accessdate=March 14, 2019|date=March 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was initially reported that the series would be released on May 30, 2019,<ref name=\"OriginalReleaseDate\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/05/01/heres-everything-coming-to-netflix-in-may-and-what-to-watch/|title=Here's Everything Coming To Netflix In May And What To Watch|last=Kain|first=Erik|date=May 1, 2019|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=May 15, 2019|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515060752/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/05/01/heres-everything-coming-to-netflix-in-may-and-what-to-watch/|archivedate=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref name=\"OriginalReleaseDate2\">{{Cite news|url=https://nerdist.com/article/everything-streaming-on-netflix-hulu-and-amazon-in-may/|title=Everything Streaming on Netflix, Hulu, and Amazon in May|last=Knight|first=Rosie|date=2019-05-02|work=Nerdist|access-date=2019-05-14|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514182821/https://nerdist.com/article/everything-streaming-on-netflix-hulu-and-amazon-in-may/|archivedate=2019-05-14}}</ref> but it instead premiered on September 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vorel|first=Jim|title=Exclusive: Netflix to Unveil Its Animated Last Kids on Earth Zombie Comedy This September|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/08/last-kids-on-earth-netflix-premiere-date-review.html|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|accessdate=August 20, 2019|date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\n\n[[Jakks Pacific]] will launch a toyline based on the series in early 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/licensing/jakks-named-master-toy-for-last-kids-on-earth-from-atomic-cartoons-cyber-group/|title=JAKKS Named Master Toy for \u2018Last Kids on Earth\u2019 from Atomic Cartoons, Cyber Group|first=Mercedes|last=Milligan|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=November 6, 2019|work=[[Animation Magazine]]}}</ref> Outright Games will publish a video game tie-in across consoles and PC in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/atomic-cartoons-and-cyber-group-developing-last-kids-earth-game|title=Atomic Cartoons and Cyber Group Developing \u2018The Last Kids on Earth\u2019 Game|date=October 31, 2019|accessdate=November 6, 2019|work=[[Animation World Network]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|8914012}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Last Kids on Earth (TV series), The}}\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s Canadian animated television series]]\n[[Category:2019 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:American television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix children's programming]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Netflix Animation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = The Last Kids On Earth \n| image             = File:The Last Kids on Earth.jpg\n| caption           = Promotional poster\n| genre             = <!-- Must be reliably sourced -->\n| creator           =\n| based_on          = {{based_on|[[The Last Kids on Earth]]||[[Max Brallier]]}}\n| writer            = \n| director          = William Lau (book 1)<br>Steve Rolston (book 2)\n| story             = \n| starring          = Nick Wolfhard\n| composer          = Marcelo Trevino\n| country           = United States <br> Canada\n| language          = English \n| num_seasons       = 2\n| num_episodes      = 11\n| list_episodes     = #Episodes\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Max Brallier\n* Scott Peterson\n* Jennifer McCarron\n* [[Matthew Berkowitz]]\n}}\n| producer = \n| location =\n| cinematography =\n| editor = \n| camera =\n| runtime = 60 minutes (book 1)<br>23 minutes (book 2)\n| picture_format = [[HDTV]] [[1080p]]\n| audio_format = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| company = [[Atomic Cartoons]]\n| distributor =\n| network = [[Netflix]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2019|09|17}}\n| last_aired = present\n| website = https://www.netflix.com/title/80219119\n| website_title = Official website\n}}\n\n'''''The Last Kids on Earth''''' is an American-Canadian [[children's television series|children's]] [[Animated series|animation]] [[web television]] series, based on the [[The Last Kids on Earth|book series of the same name]] by [[Max Brallier]], that premiered on [[Netflix]] on September 17, 2019. A ten-episode second season, or \"Book 2\", titled ''The Last Kids on Earth and the Zombie Parade'', premiered on April 17, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/netflix-trailers-the-last-kids-on-earth-season-2/|title=Netflix Trailers 'The Last Kids on Earth' Season 2|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|date=April 3, 2020|work=[[Animation Magazine]]|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of book two's tenth episode, it was announced that the series will return for a third book / season.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n* Nick Wolfhard as Jack Sullivan, a 13-year-old orphan and video gamer turned hero thanks to the apocalypse.\n* [[Charles Demers]] as Dirk Savage, a former school bully turned strongman and monster fighter on Jack's team. He likes cooking and gardening. \n* Montserrat Hernandez as June Del Toro, a tomboyish 13-year-old girl who is Jack's crush but did not reciprocate his feelings, but starts to develop some in book 2. She was trying to survive on her own until her parents come back for her with a rescue party; but she joins Jack's team and learns to have fun during the apocalypse. She was editor in chief of the school's paper.\n* Garland Whitt as Quint Baker, Jack's nerdy best friend who invents most of the gadgets the kids use to survive in their post-apocalyptic environment.\n* [[Brian Drummond]] as the vocal effects for Rover, a blue-furred canine-like monster who befriends Jack in Book 1 and becomes the team's pet and mascot.\n* [[Mark Hamill]] as Bardle, a gruff monster conjurer that takes up residence in Joe's Pizza<ref name=oller>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/mark-hamill-rosario-dawson-last-kids-on-earth-reveal|title=First Look: Mark Hamill and Rosario Dawson Have a Monster Good Time in The Last Kids on Earth|last=Oller|first=Jacob|date=April 15, 2020|website=Syfy Wire|publisher=[[Syfy]]|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Catherine O'Hara]] as Skaelka, a female monster warrior that takes up residence in Joe's Pizza and becomes a friend of June's<ref name=trumbore>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/last-kids-on-earth-netflix-season-2-cast-images-bruce-campbell-catherine-ohara/|title=Exclusive: 'The Last Kids on Earth' Season 2 Characters Revealed in First-Look Images|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|date=April 13, 2020|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Keith David]] as Thrull, the main antagonist of book two. \n* [[Bruce Campbell]] as Chef, a cranky monster that takes up residence in Joe's Pizza<ref name=trumbore /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/tv/3612967/heres-new-monster-voiced-bruce-campbell-netflixs-last-kids-earth-image/|title=Here's the New Monster Being Voiced by Bruce Campbell in Netflix's \"The Last Kids on Earth\" [Image]|last=Squires|first=John|date=April 14, 2020|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Rosario Dawson]] as Rezzoch<ref name=oller />, the main antagonist of the series as revealed in the Book 2 finale episode.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#000000 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web |title=The Last Kids on Earth \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/last-kids-on-earth/listings/ |website=The Futon Critic |accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> |released=y |country=US |episodes=\n{{Episode table/part|p=Book 1|c=#000|nopart=y}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = The Last Kids on Earth\n |DirectedBy      = Will Lau\n |WrittenBy       = Max Brallier & Scott Peterson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = Living solo in his recently-monster-infested town, 13-year-old Jack will have to think fast, find friends and get creative if he wants to survive.\n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode table/part|p=Book 2|c=#000|nopart=y}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = Mall Quest\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Max Brallier\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = Jack the Slayer\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = Jennifer Muro\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n |ShortSummary    = \n |LineColor       = 000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = Bestiary Master\n |DirectedBy      = Steve Rolston\n |WrittenBy       = 