r's book series ''The Last Kids on Earth'' with the intention of producing an animated television series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McLean|first1=Tom|title=Atomic Brings 'The Last Kids on Earth' To TV|url=https://www.awn.com/news/atomic-brings-last-kids-earth-tv|website=Animation World Network|accessdate=February 28, 2018|language=en|date=September 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Whyte|first=Alexandra|title=Atomic Cartoons options The Last Kids on Earth|url=http://kidscreen.com/2017/09/26/atomic-cartoons-options-the-last-kids-on-earth/|website=Kidscreen|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=September 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 26, 2018, it was announced that Netflix had given the production a series order. Executive producers include Brallier, Scott Peterson, Jennifer McCarron, and [[Matthew Berkowitz]]. Brallier and Peterson are also expected to write the series as well. Production companies involved in the series include [[Thunderbird Entertainment]]'s animation studio [[Atomic Cartoons]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title='The Last Kids On Earth' Animated Comedy Series Based On Books Ordered By Netflix|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/the-last-kids-on-earth-animated-comedy-series-based-books-netflix-1202305024/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=February 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Netflix Orders Animated Series 'The Last Kids on Earth'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/netflix-orders-animated-series-last-kids-earth-1089632|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=February 28, 2018|language=en|date=February 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2019, the series cast was announced, including [[Mark Hamill]], [[Rosario Dawson]], [[Catherine O'Hara]], [[Keith David]], [[Bruce Campbell]], Garland Whitt, Montserrat Hernandez, Charles Demers, and Nick Wolfhard as the lead character Jack Sullivan.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|title=\u2018The Last Kids On Earth\u2019: Mark Hamill, Rosario Dawson, Catherine O\u2019Hara and Others Set For Netflix Animated Series|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-last-kids-on-earth-netflix-mark-hamill-rosario-dawson-catherine-ohara-keith-david-bruce-campbell-garland-whitt-montse-hernandez-charles-demers-nick-wolfhard-1202574577|website=Deadline|accessdate=March 14, 2019|date=March 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was initially reported that the series would be released on May 30, 2019,<ref name=\"OriginalReleaseDate\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/05/01/heres-everything-coming-to-netflix-in-may-and-what-to-watch/|title=Here's Everything Coming To Netflix In May And What To Watch|last=Kain|first=Erik|date=May 1, 2019|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=May 15, 2019|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515060752/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/05/01/heres-everything-coming-to-netflix-in-may-and-what-to-watch/|archivedate=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref name=\"OriginalReleaseDate2\">{{Cite news|url=https://nerdist.com/article/everything-streaming-on-netflix-hulu-and-amazon-in-may/|title=Everything Streaming on Netflix, Hulu, and Amazon in May|last=Knight|first=Rosie|date=2019-05-02|work=Nerdist|access-date=2019-05-14|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514182821/https://nerdist.com/article/everything-streaming-on-netflix-hulu-and-amazon-in-may/|archivedate=2019-05-14}}</ref> but it instead premiered on September 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vorel|first=Jim|title=Exclusive: Netflix to Unveil Its Animated Last Kids on Earth Zombie Comedy This September|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/08/last-kids-on-earth-netflix-premiere-date-review.html|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|accessdate=August 20, 2019|date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\n\n[[Jakks Pacific]] will launch a toyline based on the series in early 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/licensing/jakks-named-master-toy-for-last-kids-on-earth-from-atomic-cartoons-cyber-group/|title=JAKKS Named Master Toy for \u2018Last Kids on Earth\u2019 from Atomic Cartoons, Cyber Group|first=Mercedes|last=Milligan|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=November 6, 2019|work=[[Animation Magazine]]}}</ref> Outright Games will publish a video game tie-in across consoles and PC in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/atomic-cartoons-and-cyber-group-developing-last-kids-earth-game|title=Atomic Cartoons and Cyber Group Developing \u2018The Last Kids on Earth\u2019 Game|date=October 31, 2019|accessdate=November 6, 2019|work=[[Animation World Network]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|8914012}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Last Kids on Earth (TV series), The}}\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s Canadian animated television series]]\n[[Category:2019 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:American television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix children's programming]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Netflix Animation]]\n", "name_user": "Prince Silversaddle", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Last_Kids_on_Earth_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "American Association of Law Libraries", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n|name           = American Association of Law Libraries\n|image          = \n|image_border   = \n|size           = \n|alt            = \n|caption        = \n|map            = \n|msize          = \n|malt           = \n|mcaption       = \n|map2           =\n|abbreviation   = AALL\n|motto          = \n|mission        =\n|predecessor    =\n|successor      =\n|formation      = 1906\n|founded        = \n|founder        = A.J. Small\n|extinction     = \n|type           = \n|status         = Nonprofit educational organization\n|purpose        = \n|professional_title = <!-- for professional associations -->\n|headquarters   = [[Chicago]], IL\n|location       = \n|coords         = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n|region_served  = [[United States]]\n|services       = \n|membership     = 5,000\n|member         =\n|language       = \n|general        =\n|leader_title   = \n|leader_name    = \n|leader_title2  = \n|leader_name2   =\n|leader_title3  =\n|leader_name3   =\n|leader_title4  =\n|leader_name4   = \n|key_people     =\n|main_organ     = \n|parent_organization = \n|subsidiaries   = \n|affiliations   = \n|budget         = \n|num_staff      = \n|num_volunteers = \n|slogan         = \n|website        = {{URL|http://www.aallnet.org}}\n|remarks        = \n|footnotes      = \n|former name    =\n}}\nThe '''American Association of Law Libraries''' \"is a [[nonprofit]] educational organization with over 5,000 members nationwide. AALL's mission is to promote and enhance the value of [[law libraries]] to the legal and public communities, to foster the profession of [[law librarian]]ship, and to provide leadership in the field of legal information and information policy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/2006/08/eff-aclu-american-association-of-law.html |title=EFF, ACLU, American Association of Law Libraries, Public Citizen, ACLU of Oklahoma, Come to Aid of Deborah Foster, File Amicus Brief in Support |publisher=Recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com |date=2006-08-13 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>\n\n==History and vision==\nAALL was founded in 1906.<ref>{{cite web|title=AALL chronology|url=http://www.aallnet.org/top-menu/about/aall-chronology.pdf|accessdate=9 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530190607/http://aallnet.org/top-menu/about/aall-chronology.pdf|archive-date=30 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The American Association of Law Libraries' vision is to be \n<blockquote>\"a thriving professional association whose members and libraries-whether physical or virtual legal information services-are recognized as critical to the success of their organizations and as central to society. AALL members possess the knowledge and skills to maintain effectiveness in a constantly changing legal environment. Since the ready availability of legal information is a necessary requirement for a just and [[democratic society]], AALL and its members advocate and work toward fair and equitable access to authentic current and historic legal information, and educate and train library users to be knowledgeable and skilled legal information consumers.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=American Association of Law Libraries|url=http://www.aallnet.org/top-menu/about|accessdate=10 October 2013|authorlink=About Us}}</ref> </blockquote>The first president of the AALL was Arthur James Small (1869-1937), who was elected at the association's formation on July 2, 1906.  Small was a law librarian at the Iowa State Library, and it was his idea to create an organization separate from the American Library Association specifically for law librarianship.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Houdek|first=F. G.|date=2006|title=AALL history through the eyes of its presidents|url=|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=98|issue=2|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>  Small never graduated high school or attended college, yet he successfully served the Iowa State Library for over forty years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Houdek|first=F. G.|date=2006|title=Frequently asked questions about AALL's first hundred years|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-98/pub_llj_v98n01/2006-06.pdf|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=98|issue=1|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911113116/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-98/pub_llj_v98n01/2006-06.pdf|archive-date=2016-09-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrederick C. Hicks (1875-1956) was another early president who greatly contributed to the AALL's vision.  Hicks was a law librarian at both Yale and Columbia.  In 1919, Hicks was first elected president of the AALL.  He served two terms as president, 1919-1920 and 1920-1921.  In 1923, Hicks authored ''Materials and Methods of Legal Research''.  Prior to the publication of this book, there were very few legal research texts keeping pace with the explosive growth in casebooks and legal literature.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Etheredge|first=S.|date=2006|title=Frederick C. Hicks: The dean of law librarians|url=|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=98|issue=2|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>  Hicks was also a major proponent of expanding the scope of the AALL's ''Law Library Journal''.  Prior to Hicks's input, the ''Journal'' mostly served as a depository for AALL committee reports.  Hicks believed an expanded ''Journal'' could cover multiple aspects of law librarianship, ranging from scholarly articles to industry news.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Butler|first=A. H.|date=2006|title=Frederick Hicks's strategic vision for law librarianship|url=http://aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-98/pub_llj_v98n02/2006-19.pdf|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=98|issue=2|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913140552/http://aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-98/pub_llj_v98n02/2006-19.pdf|archive-date=2016-09-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first woman to be elected AALL president was [[Rosamond Parma]] (1884-1946).  She served two terms from 1930 to 1932.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Member-Resources/AALLawards/award-hof/Hall-of-Fame-Members/Parma.html|title=Rosamond Parma, 1884-1946|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915180825/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Member-Resources/AALLawards/award-hof/Hall-of-Fame-Members/Parma.html|archive-date=2015-09-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Parma was also the first law librarian for the University of California, serving as director of UC Berkeley's Boalt Hall library from 1911 to 1935.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cla-net.org/page/988/California-Library-Hall-of-Fame-Rosamond-Parma.htm|title=California Library Hall of Fame: Rosamond Parma|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>  She also managed the ''California Law Review''.<ref>{{Cite journal|orig-year=1947|title=Rosamond Parma, 1884-1946|journal=California Law Review|volume=35|issue=1|page=91|jstor=}}</ref>\n\nHarry Bitner (1916-2001), who served as president for 1963-1964, helped elevate the position of law librarian from an under-educated service position to today's highly skilled specialists.  Bitner outlined his thoughts in a ''Law Library Journal'' essay titled \"The Educational Background of the University's Law Librarian\" where he advocated college, library school, and law school degrees for new law librarians.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vinson|first=J.|date=2010|title=Fostering the profession of law: The lifetime achievements of Harry Bitner|url=|journal=Legal Reference Services Quarterly|volume=29|issue=2|doi=10.1080/02703191003751222|pmid=|access-date=|via=}}</ref>  In 1953, Bitner, along with Miles O. Price, authored ''Effective Legal Research''.  This work updated and advanced many of the themes first presented in Hick's ''Materials and Methods of Legal Research''.  As president, Bitner was instrumental in establishing a permanent headquarters for the AALL.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=M. L.|date=2002|title=Harry Bitner: A memorial|url=http://aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-94/pub_llj_v94n02/2002-14.pdf|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=94|issue=2|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021175036/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-94/pub_llj_v94n02/2002-14.pdf|archive-date=2015-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Advocacy==\nThe AALL and its members have a long history of proactively influencing policy initiatives in the legal information field.  The 1970s were the beginning of the modern era of AALL advocacy.  This decade saw the association helping to provide input and shape several important policy issues such as the 1975 Federal Trade Commission's ''Guides for the Law Book Industry'', the ''[[Copyright Act of 1976]]'', and the 1972 and 1978 amendments to [[Title 44 of the United States Code]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baish|first=M. A.|year=2003|title=AALL's advocacy program gets better all the time. . . with a lot of help from its members|journal=AALL Spectrum|volume=7|issue=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, AALL's Government Relations Office staff, along with local chapters and AALL members, held the first Local Advocate Lobby Day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aallnet.org/Documents/Government-Relations/LobbyDay2013.pdf|title=Lobby Day 2013|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520114920/http://www.aallnet.org/Documents/Government-Relations/LobbyDay2013.pdf|archive-date=2013-05-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>  This event consists of visits to House and Senate offices to raise the profile of information policy issues pertinent to the AALL.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Feltren|first=E.|date=2015|title=AALL Lobby Day Paves the Way for Successful Advocacy Relationships|journal=AALL Spectrum|volume=19|issue=7}}</ref>\n\nAALL took a strong position against the [[Federal Register Modernization Act (H.R. 4195; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would require the ''[[Federal Register]]'' to be published (e.g., by electronic means), rather than printed, and that documents in the ''Federal Register'' be made available for sale or distribution to the public in published form.<ref name=\"4195sum\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 4195 - Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4195|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref> AALL argued that the bill \"undermines\" citizens' \"right to be informed\" by making it more difficult for \"citizens to find their government's regulations.\"<ref name=\"AALLoppose\">{{cite web|title=The Federal Register and Code of Federal Regulations|url=http://aallnet.org/Documents/Government-Relations/Issue-Briefs-and-Reports/2014/FRonepager.pdf|publisher=American Association of Law Libraries|accessdate=14 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715020300/http://aallnet.org/Documents/Government-Relations/Issue-Briefs-and-Reports/2014/FRonepager.pdf|archive-date=2014-07-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> According to AALL, a survey they conducted \"revealed that members of the public, librarians, researchers, students, attorneys, and small business owners continue to rely on the print\" version of the ''Federal Register''.<ref name=\"AALLoppose\" /> AALL also argued that the lack of print versions of the ''Federal Register'' and ''CFR'' would mean the 15 percent of Americans who don't use the internet would lose their access to that material.<ref name=\"AALLoppose\" />\n\nAccess to Legal Information. The American Association of Law Libraries has been supporting free access to Pacer information for decades. In February 2019 the AALL joined with 15 organization and signed a letter calling for passage of H.R. 6714 the Electronic Records Reform Act. In addition to requiring free access to the federal dockets and documents, the legislation  directs the Administrative Office of the US Courts to consolidate the Case Management/Electronic Case Files system into a single system.<ref>https://www.aallnet.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/ECRRA-House-021219.pdf</ref> Additionally this year the AALL joined the American Civil Liberties Union and several other organizations on an amicus brief in response to National Veterans Legal Services Program et al v. United States of America supporting the idea that the First Amendment guarantees the public a right of access to judicial records through PACER. The case is currently before the United States Courts of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.<ref>https://www.aallnet.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/In-Support-of-Cross-Appellees-National-Veterans-Legal-Services-Program.pdf</ref>\n\n==Publication==\nThe primary publication produced by AALL is the quarterly '''''[[Law Library Journal]]'''''.  In 1907, Frederick W. Schenk made the recommendation for both a quarterly journal and index.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2008|title=A Law Library Journal centennial timeline: Highlights from one hundred years of LLJ history|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-100/pub_llj_v100n03/2008-24.pdf|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=100|issue=3|pages=541\u2013554|access-date=2016-10-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151020074439/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-100/pub_llj_v100n03/2008-24.pdf|archive-date=2015-10-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The ''Law Library Journal'' has been the official publication of AALL since 1908 and contains scholarly articles on law, legal materials, legal research, and librarianship. The AALL also produces a monthly magazine, The ''AALL Spectrum''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aallnet.org/main-menu/Publications/llj |title=American Association of Law Libraries Law Library Journal |publisher=Aallnet.org |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208041618/http://aallnet.org/main-menu/Publications/llj |archive-date=2014-02-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Furthermore, the AALL was the first publisher of the ''Index to Legal Periodicals'', including it with the ''[[Law Library Journal]]'' beginning in 1908.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aallnet.org/tm/about/aall-chronology.pdf |title=AALL Chronology |publisher=AALL |date= |accessdate=2014-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022034548/http://www.aallnet.org/tm/about/aall-chronology.pdf |archive-date=2014-10-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Printing of the ''Index to Legal Periodicals'' was passed to the [[H. W. Wilson Company|H.W. Wilson Company]] in April 1912, and the company assumed business management duties of the ''Index'' in 1914.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aallnet.org/tm/about/aall-chronology.pdf |title=AALL Chronology |publisher=AALL |date= |accessdate=2014-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022034548/http://www.aallnet.org/tm/about/aall-chronology.pdf |archive-date=2014-10-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The AALL publishes a monthly eNewsletter, as well as periodic eBriefings.  Many current AALL publications, such as ''AALL Biennial Salary Survey'', ''AALL Price Index for Legal Publications'', and ''Guide to Fair Business Practices'' are focused on law librarianship advocacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/publications|title=Publications|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>  AALL also produces the ''[[Index to Foreign Legal Periodicals]]'', an index providing multilingual coverage of foreign, international, and comparative legal journals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/products/Index-to-Foreign-Legal-Periodicals.html |title=Index to Foreign Legal Periodicals |publisher=AALL |date= |accessdate=2014-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020105925/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/products/Index-to-Foreign-Legal-Periodicals.html |archive-date=2014-10-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Law}}\n*[[List of sources of law in the United States]]\n*[[Public Law Libraries (U.S.)]]\n*[[Law Library]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.aallnet.org American Association of Law Libraries (AALL) website]\n*[http://crivblog.com The CRIV Blog: The Official Blog of the Committee on Relations with Information Vendors]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Legal research]]\n[[Category:Library-related professional associations]]\n[[Category:Law libraries]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1906]]\n[[Category:1906 establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n|name           = American Association of Law Libraries\n|image          = \n|image_border   = \n|size           = \n|alt            = \n|caption        = \n|map            = \n|msize          = \n|malt           = \n|mcaption       = \n|map2           =\n|abbreviation   = AALL\n|motto          = \n|mission        =\n|predecessor    =\n|successor      =\n|formation      = 1906\n|founded        = \n|founder        = A.J. Small\n|extinction     = \n|type           = \n|status         = Nonprofit educational organization\n|purpose        = \n|professional_title = <!-- for professional associations -->\n|headquarters   = [[Chicago]], IL\n|location       = \n|coords         = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n|region_served  = [[United States]]\n|services       = \n|membership     = 5,000\n|member         =\n|language       = \n|general        =\n|leader_title   = \n|leader_name    = \n|leader_title2  = \n|leader_name2   =\n|leader_title3  =\n|leader_name3   =\n|leader_title4  =\n|leader_name4   = \n|key_people     =\n|main_organ     = \n|parent_organization = \n|subsidiaries   = \n|affiliations   = \n|budget         = \n|num_staff      = \n|num_volunteers = \n|slogan         = \n|website        = {{URL|http://www.aallnet.org}}\n|remarks        = \n|footnotes      = \n|former name    =\n}}\nThe '''American Association of Law Libraries''' \"is a [[nonprofit]] educational organization with over 5,000 members nationwide. AALL's mission is to promote and enhance the value of [[law libraries]] to the legal and public communities, to foster the profession of [[law librarian]]ship, and to provide leadership in the field of legal information and information policy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/2006/08/eff-aclu-american-association-of-law.html |title=EFF, ACLU, American Association of Law Libraries, Public Citizen, ACLU of Oklahoma, Come to Aid of Deborah Foster, File Amicus Brief in Support |publisher=Recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com |date=2006-08-13 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>\n\n==History and vision==\nAALL was founded in 1906.<ref>{{cite web|title=AALL chronology|url=http://www.aallnet.org/top-menu/about/aall-chronology.pdf|accessdate=9 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530190607/http://aallnet.org/top-menu/about/aall-chronology.pdf|archive-date=30 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The American Association of Law Libraries' vision is to be \n<blockquote>\"a thriving professional association whose members and libraries-whether physical or virtual legal information services-are recognized as critical to the success of their organizations and as central to society. AALL members possess the knowledge and skills to maintain effectiveness in a constantly changing legal environment. Since the ready availability of legal information is a necessary requirement for a just and [[democratic society]], AALL and its members advocate and work toward fair and equitable access to authentic current and historic legal information, and educate and train library users to be knowledgeable and skilled legal information consumers.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=American Association of Law Libraries|url=http://www.aallnet.org/top-menu/about|accessdate=10 October 2013|authorlink=About Us}}</ref> </blockquote>The first president of the AALL was Arthur James Small (1869-1937), who was elected at the association's formation on July 2, 1906.  Small was a law librarian at the Iowa State Library, and it was his idea to create an organization separate from the American Library Association specifically for law librarianship.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Houdek|first=F. G.|date=2006|title=AALL history through the eyes of its presidents|url=|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=98|issue=2|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>  Small never graduated high school or attended college, yet he successfully served the Iowa State Library for over forty years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Houdek|first=F. G.|date=2006|title=Frequently asked questions about AALL's first hundred years|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-98/pub_llj_v98n01/2006-06.pdf|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=98|issue=1|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911113116/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-98/pub_llj_v98n01/2006-06.pdf|archive-date=2016-09-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrederick C. Hicks (1875-1956) was another early president who greatly contributed to the AALL's vision.  Hicks was a law librarian at both Yale and Columbia.  In 1919, Hicks was first elected president of the AALL.  He served two terms as president, 1919-1920 and 1920-1921.  In 1923, Hicks authored ''Materials and Methods of Legal Research''.  Prior to the publication of this book, there were very few legal research texts keeping pace with the explosive growth in casebooks and legal literature.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Etheredge|first=S.|date=2006|title=Frederick C. Hicks: The dean of law librarians|url=|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=98|issue=2|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>  Hicks was also a major proponent of expanding the scope of the AALL's ''Law Library Journal''.  Prior to Hicks's input, the ''Journal'' mostly served as a depository for AALL committee reports.  Hicks believed an expanded ''Journal'' could cover multiple aspects of law librarianship, ranging from scholarly articles to industry news.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Butler|first=A. H.|date=2006|title=Frederick Hicks's strategic vision for law librarianship|url=http://aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-98/pub_llj_v98n02/2006-19.pdf|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=98|issue=2|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913140552/http://aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-98/pub_llj_v98n02/2006-19.pdf|archive-date=2016-09-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first woman to be elected AALL president was [[Rosamond Parma]] (1884-1946).  She served two terms from 1930 to 1932.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Member-Resources/AALLawards/award-hof/Hall-of-Fame-Members/Parma.html|title=Rosamond Parma, 1884-1946|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915180825/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Member-Resources/AALLawards/award-hof/Hall-of-Fame-Members/Parma.html|archive-date=2015-09-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Parma was also the first law librarian for the University of California, serving as director of UC Berkeley's Boalt Hall library from 1911 to 1935.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cla-net.org/page/988/California-Library-Hall-of-Fame-Rosamond-Parma.htm|title=California Library Hall of Fame: Rosamond Parma|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>  She also managed the ''California Law Review''.<ref>{{Cite journal|orig-year=1947|title=Rosamond Parma, 1884-1946|journal=California Law Review|volume=35|issue=1|page=91|jstor=}}</ref>\n\nHarry Bitner (1916-2001), who served as president for 1963-1964, helped elevate the position of law librarian from an under-educated service position to today's highly skilled specialists.  Bitner outlined his thoughts in a ''Law Library Journal'' essay titled \"The Educational Background of the University's Law Librarian\" where he advocated college, library school, and law school degrees for new law librarians.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vinson|first=J.|date=2010|title=Fostering the profession of law: The lifetime achievements of Harry Bitner|url=|journal=Legal Reference Services Quarterly|volume=29|issue=2|doi=10.1080/02703191003751222|pmid=|access-date=|via=}}</ref>  In 1953, Bitner, along with Miles O. Price, authored ''Effective Legal Research''.  This work updated and advanced many of the themes first presented in Hick's ''Materials and Methods of Legal Research''.  As president, Bitner was instrumental in establishing a permanent headquarters for the AALL.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=M. L.|date=2002|title=Harry Bitner: A memorial|url=http://aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-94/pub_llj_v94n02/2002-14.pdf|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=94|issue=2|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021175036/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-94/pub_llj_v94n02/2002-14.pdf|archive-date=2015-10-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Advocacy==\nThe AALL and its members have a long history of proactively influencing policy initiatives in the legal information field.  The 1970s were the beginning of the modern era of AALL advocacy.  This decade saw the association helping to provide input and shape several important policy issues such as the 1975 Federal Trade Commission's ''Guides for the Law Book Industry'', the ''[[Copyright Act of 1976]]'', and the 1972 and 1978 amendments to [[Title 44 of the United States Code]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baish|first=M. A.|year=2003|title=AALL's advocacy program gets better all the time. . . with a lot of help from its members|journal=AALL Spectrum|volume=7|issue=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, AALL's Government Relations Office staff, along with local chapters and AALL members, held the first Local Advocate Lobby Day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aallnet.org/Documents/Government-Relations/LobbyDay2013.pdf|title=Lobby Day 2013|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520114920/http://www.aallnet.org/Documents/Government-Relations/LobbyDay2013.pdf|archive-date=2013-05-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>  This event consists of visits to House and Senate offices to raise the profile of information policy issues pertinent to the AALL.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Feltren|first=E.|date=2015|title=AALL Lobby Day Paves the Way for Successful Advocacy Relationships|journal=AALL Spectrum|volume=19|issue=7}}</ref>\n\nAALL took a strong position against the [[Federal Register Modernization Act (H.R. 4195; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would require the ''[[Federal Register]]'' to be published (e.g., by electronic means), rather than printed, and that documents in the ''Federal Register'' be made available for sale or distribution to the public in published form.<ref name=\"4195sum\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 4195 - Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4195|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref> AALL argued that the bill \"undermines\" citizens' \"right to be informed\" by making it more difficult for \"citizens to find their government's regulations.\"<ref name=\"AALLoppose\">{{cite web|title=The Federal Register and Code of Federal Regulations|url=http://aallnet.org/Documents/Government-Relations/Issue-Briefs-and-Reports/2014/FRonepager.pdf|publisher=American Association of Law Libraries|accessdate=14 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715020300/http://aallnet.org/Documents/Government-Relations/Issue-Briefs-and-Reports/2014/FRonepager.pdf|archive-date=2014-07-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> According to AALL, a survey they conducted \"revealed that members of the public, librarians, researchers, students, attorneys, and small business owners continue to rely on the print\" version of the ''Federal Register''.<ref name=\"AALLoppose\" /> AALL also argued that the lack of print versions of the ''Federal Register'' and ''CFR'' would mean the 15 percent of Americans who don't use the internet would lose their access to that material.<ref name=\"AALLoppose\" />\n\nAccess to Legal Information. The American Association of Law Libraries has been supporting free access to Pacer information for decades. In February 2019 the AALL joined with 15 organization and signed a letter calling for passage of H.R. 6714 the Electronic Records Reform Act. In addition to requiring free access to the federal dockets and documents, the legislation  directs the Administrative Office of the US Courts to consolidate the Case Management/Electronic Case Files system into a single system.<ref>https://www.aallnet.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/ECRRA-House-021219.pdf</ref> Additionally this year the AALL joined the American Civil Liberties Union and several other organizations on an amicus brief in response to National Veterans Legal Services Program et al v. United States of America supporting the idea that the First Amendment guarantees the public a right of access to judicial records through PACER. The case is currently before the United States Courts of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.<ref>https://www.aallnet.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/In-Support-of-Cross-Appellees-National-Veterans-Legal-Services-Program.pdf</ref>\n\n==Publication==\nThe primary publication produced by AALL is the quarterly '''''[[Law Library Journal]]'''''.  In 1907, Frederick W. Schenk made the recommendation for both a quarterly journal and index.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2008|title=A Law Library Journal centennial timeline: Highlights from one hundred years of LLJ history|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-100/pub_llj_v100n03/2008-24.pdf|journal=Law Library Journal|volume=100|issue=3|pages=541\u2013554|access-date=2016-10-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151020074439/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/llj/LLJ-Archives/Vol-100/pub_llj_v100n03/2008-24.pdf|archive-date=2015-10-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The ''Law Library Journal'' has been the official publication of AALL since 1908 and contains scholarly articles on law, legal materials, legal research, and librarianship. The AALL also produces a monthly magazine, The ''AALL Spectrum''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aallnet.org/main-menu/Publications/llj |title=American Association of Law Libraries Law Library Journal |publisher=Aallnet.org |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208041618/http://aallnet.org/main-menu/Publications/llj |archive-date=2014-02-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Furthermore, the AALL was the first publisher of the ''Index to Legal Periodicals'', including it with the ''[[Law Library Journal]]'' beginning in 1908.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aallnet.org/tm/about/aall-chronology.pdf |title=AALL Chronology |publisher=AALL |date= |accessdate=2014-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022034548/http://www.aallnet.org/tm/about/aall-chronology.pdf |archive-date=2014-10-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Printing of the ''Index to Legal Periodicals'' was passed to the [[H. W. Wilson Company|H.W. Wilson Company]] in April 1912, and the company assumed business management duties of the ''Index'' in 1914.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aallnet.org/tm/about/aall-chronology.pdf |title=AALL Chronology |publisher=AALL |date= |accessdate=2014-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022034548/http://www.aallnet.org/tm/about/aall-chronology.pdf |archive-date=2014-10-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The AALL publishes a monthly eNewsletter, as well as periodic eBriefings.  Many current AALL publications, such as ''AALL Biennial Salary Survey'', ''AALL Price Index for Legal Publications'', and ''Guide to Fair Business Practices'' are focused on law librarianship advocacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/publications|title=Publications|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>  AALL also produces the ''[[Index to Foreign Legal Periodicals]]'', an index providing multilingual coverage of foreign, international, and comparative legal journals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/products/Index-to-Foreign-Legal-Periodicals.html |title=Index to Foreign Legal Periodicals |publisher=AALL |date= |accessdate=2014-10-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020105925/http://www.aallnet.org/mm/Publications/products/Index-to-Foreign-Legal-Periodicals.html |archive-date=2014-10-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Law}}\n*[[List of sources of law in the United States]]\n*[[Public Law Libraries (U.S.)]]\n*[[Law Library]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.aallnet.org American Association of Law Libraries (AALL) website]\n*[http://crivblog.com The CRIV Blog: The Official Blog of the Committee on Relations with Information Vendors]\n\n[[Category:Legal research]]\n[[Category:Library-related professional associations]]\n[[Category:Law libraries]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1906]]\n[[Category:1906 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Association_of_Law_Libraries"}
{"title_page": "Allen County Public Library", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Primary sources|date=December 2009}}\n{{Coord|41|4|37.6|N|85|8|35.5|W|region:US|display=title}}\n{{Infobox library\n| library_name = Allen County Public Library\n| image =\n| library_logo = Allen County Public Library (logo).jpg\n| location = 900 Library Plaza<br />[[Fort Wayne, Indiana]] 46802\n| country = United States\n| established = 1895\n| num_branches = 14\n| collection_size = 3,445,808\n| annual_circulation = 6 million +\n| pop_served = 365,918 (2014 estimate)\n| budget = $11,084,786\n| director = Greta Southard\n| num_employees = 317\n| website = [http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/ Allen County Public Library Website]\n}}\nThe '''Allen County Public Library''' (ACPL) is a [[Public library|public library system]] located in [[Fort Wayne, Indiana|Fort Wayne]], [[Allen County, Indiana|Allen County]], [[Indiana]], [[United States]]. Founded in 1895 as the Fort Wayne Public Library, the library served residents with 3,606 books out of a single room in [[Fort Wayne Old City Hall Building|City Hall]]. Today the library system includes 14 library branches within Fort Wayne and throughout the county. The {{convert|367000|sqft|m2}} Main Library Branch in downtown Fort Wayne is home to the Fred J. Reynolds Historical Genealogy Department, which holds the largest public [[genealogy]] collection in the United States.\n\n==Timeline==\n1895 \u2013 Library opened in City Hall on January 28 with 3,606 volumes.<br />\n1898 \u2013 Library Board purchased the Brackenridge Home at Wayne Street and Webster Street for $14,000.<br />\n1904 \u2013 [[Carnegie library|Carnegie]]-funded library building opened.<br />\n1923 \u2013 Service to county residents began. Fort Wayne Public Library became Public Library of Fort Wayne and Allen County.<br />\n1944 \u2013 Main Library expansion began with purchase of Hollywood Building on Washington Boulevard to house administrative offices.<br />\n1952 \u2013 Young Adult Department opened in basement of main library, the first such department in the country.<br />\n1968 \u2013 {{convert|173500|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building at Wayne and Webster Streets was dedicated August 21, 1968.<br />\n1977 \u2013 Construction of the new addition to the Main Library began.<br />\n1980 \u2013 Public Library of Fort Wayne and Allen County officially became Allen County Public Library by act of the state legislature on January 1.<br />\n1985 \u2013 Estimated 5,500 people ate 2,731 pizzas during system's 90th birthday celebration.<br />\n1997 \u2013 Library Board and staff began system-wide space needs analysis for all library facilities.<br />\n2001 \u2013 Allen County taxpayers approved bond financing of the $84&nbsp;million library expansion project.<br />\n2007 \u2013 Renovation and expansion of main library nears completion. Grand opening held on January 27, 2007, with Randall T. Shepard, [[Chief Justice]] of the [[Indiana Supreme Court]], among the speakers.\n\n==Genealogy==\nThe Fred J. Reynolds Historical Genealogy Department, located in the Main Library Branch, is the largest public [[genealogy]] department in North America, home to more than 350,000 printed volumes and 513,000 items of [[microfilm]] and [[microfiche]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Nick | last=West | date=2009-10-09 | url=http://www.news-sentinel.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20091002/NEWS/910020346 | title=Genealogy gathering; 420 expected for conference, library's largest yet | work=[[The News-Sentinel]] | accessdate=2010-08-09 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002083952/http://www.news-sentinel.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20091002%2FNEWS%2F910020346 | archive-date=October 2, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/genealogy/index.html |publisher=Allen County Public Library |title=Genealogy Center |accessdate=2010-08-09 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808214830/http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/genealogy/index.html |archivedate=August 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> Only the [[Family History Library]] in [[Salt Lake City]], a private institution, is larger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lds.org/placestovisit/location/0,10634,1869-1-1-1,00.html |publisher=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints |title=Family History Library |accessdate=2010-08-09 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809124023/http://www.lds.org/placestovisit/location/0%2C10634%2C1869-1-1-1%2C00.html |archivedate=August 9, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Allen County Public Library is also a partner of [[Werelate.org|WeRelate]], a collaborative online genealogy database currently providing access to over one million records and two million person pages. The website also provides the largest documented place wiki available.\n\n==Branches==\nTen of the Allen County Public Library's branches are located within Fort Wayne. Four branches are located in municipalities within Allen County (the name of the communities these four branches are located in is indicated next to each library's name).\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n* Aboite Branch\n* Dupont Branch\n* Georgetown Branch\n* Grabill Branch ([[Grabill, Indiana|Grabill]])\n* Hessen Cassel Branch\n* Little Turtle Branch\n* Main Branch\n{{col-break|width=65%}}\n* Monroeville Branch ([[Monroeville, Indiana|Monroeville]])\n* New Haven Branch ([[New Haven, Indiana|New Haven]])\n* Pontiac Branch\n* Shawnee Branch\n* Tecumseh Branch\n* Waynedale Branch\n* Woodburn Branch ([[Woodburn, Indiana|Woodburn]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Facilities==\nThe Main Library has five public meeting rooms that accommodate from six to 500 people. These rooms are available for use by the community for meetings and events. In addition, the building has six small group study rooms, a computer training room, and a theater which seats 230. Library branches also have meeting rooms and study rooms. The Main Library and the Georgetown branch have Maker Labs.\n\n===Access Fort Wayne===\nAccess Fort Wayne (AFW) is a [[Public-access television]] cable TV station which provides a variety of unique services for the library. AFW originates three Public-access television channels from the Main Library. Access 1 is channel 25 on [[Verizon]] and 55 on [[Comcast]]. Access 2 is channel 27 on Verizon and 57 on Comcast. [[Government-access television]] (GATV), City TV is channel 28 on Verizon and 58 on Comcast. The channels can only be viewed on Comcast and Verizon inside of Allen County. AFW is a full production facility with two TV studios and editing facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/afw/index.html |title=Allen County Public Library: Access Fort Wayne |publisher=Acpl.lib.in.us |date= |accessdate=2011-12-02}}</ref>\n\n===Audio Reading Service===\nFounded in 1979 as the Northeast Indiana Radio Reading Service (NEIRRS), the Audio Reading Service is a [[radio reading service]] for people who have visual, physical, learning, or language challenges to reading normal printed materials because of blindness, low-vision, a literacy issue, language barrier, or a physical condition. The service is for people with macular degeneration, diabetic retinopathy, arthritis, stroke, Parkinson's disease, and other conditions that affect reading traditional print. Under the leadership of library staff, volunteers read local news, grocery ads, cultural events, obituaries and other features from area newspapers, plus nearly 80 magazines and other publications.\n\nPreviously transmitted on an [[Subsidiary communications authority|SCA broadcast]], the Audio Reading Service can be heard on the [[HD Radio]] station 89.1 FM HD3, broadcast from Fort Wayne. HD Radios are loaned out at no cost by the library. In addition, the service is available via podcast, live web streaming, the Sero mobile app, and [[TuneIn]]; as a secondary audio program (SAP-French) on [[WFWA|PBS 39.4]]; and system-wide at select area healthcare facilities.<ref>https://acpl-cms.wise.oclc.org/explore/ars</ref>\n\nThe Audio Reading Service broadcasts 24 hours a day, seven days a week, and reaches an estimated 80,000 individuals. It became a part of the Allen County Public Library in 2004 and changed its name to Audio Reading Service in 2015. It is a member of the International Association of Audio Information Services (IAAIS).\n\n===WELT 95.7 FM===\nWELT-LP is a non-commercial radio station, produced and delivered by members of the Fort Wayne community. From the studios at the downtown branch of the Allen County Public Library, WELT-LP's volunteers and staff promote programs with news about politics and community issues, plus music and entertainment performed by local, regional and national artists in Fort Wayne venues.<ref>http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/home/using-the-library/start-here/access-fort-wayne/95-7-welt</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.acpl.info Allen County Public Library]\n* [http://www.genealogycenter.info The Genealogy Center of the Allen County Public Library]\n* [https://wiki.familysearch.org/en/Allen_County_Public_Library Allen County Public Library] at FamilySearch Research Wiki for genealogists\n\n{{Fort Wayne, Indiana}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1895]]\n[[Category:Education in Allen County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1904]]\n[[Category:Carnegie libraries in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Genealogical libraries]]\n[[Category:Education in Fort Wayne, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Fort Wayne, Indiana]]\n[[Category:1895 establishments in Indiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Primary sources|date=December 2009}}\n{{Coord|41|4|37.6|N|85|8|35.5|W|region:US|display=title}}\n{{Infobox library\n| library_name = Allen County Public Library\n| image =\n| library_logo = Allen County Public Library (logo).jpg\n| location = 900 Library Plaza<br />[[Fort Wayne, Indiana]] 46802\n| country = United States\n| established = 1895\n| num_branches = 14\n| collection_size = 3,445,808\n| annual_circulation = 6 million +\n| pop_served = 365,918 (2014 estimate)\n| budget = $11,084,786\n| director = Greta Southard\n| num_employees = 317\n| website = [http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/ Allen County Public Library Website]\n}}\nThe '''Allen County Public Library''' (ACPL) is a [[Public library|public library system]] located in [[Fort Wayne, Indiana|Fort Wayne]], [[Allen County, Indiana|Allen County]], [[Indiana]], [[United States]]. Founded in 1895 as the Fort Wayne Public Library, the library served residents with 3,606 books out of a single room in [[Fort Wayne Old City Hall Building|City Hall]]. Today the library system includes 14 library branches within Fort Wayne and throughout the county. The {{convert|367000|sqft|m2}} Main Library Branch in downtown Fort Wayne is home to the Fred J. Reynolds Historical Genealogy Department, which holds the largest public [[genealogy]] collection in the United States.\n\n==Timeline==\n1895 \u2013 Library opened in City Hall on January 28 with 3,606 volumes.<br />\n1898 \u2013 Library Board purchased the Brackenridge Home at Wayne Street and Webster Street for $14,000.<br />\n1904 \u2013 [[Carnegie library|Carnegie]]-funded library building opened.<br />\n1923 \u2013 Service to county residents began. Fort Wayne Public Library became Public Library of Fort Wayne and Allen County.<br />\n1944 \u2013 Main Library expansion began with purchase of Hollywood Building on Washington Boulevard to house administrative offices.<br />\n1952 \u2013 Young Adult Department opened in basement of main library, the first such department in the country.<br />\n1968 \u2013 {{convert|173500|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building at Wayne and Webster Streets was dedicated August 21, 1968.<br />\n1977 \u2013 Construction of the new addition to the Main Library began.<br />\n1980 \u2013 Public Library of Fort Wayne and Allen County officially became Allen County Public Library by act of the state legislature on January 1.<br />\n1985 \u2013 Estimated 5,500 people ate 2,731 pizzas during system's 90th birthday celebration.<br />\n1997 \u2013 Library Board and staff began system-wide space needs analysis for all library facilities.<br />\n2001 \u2013 Allen County taxpayers approved bond financing of the $84&nbsp;million library expansion project.<br />\n2007 \u2013 Renovation and expansion of main library nears completion. Grand opening held on January 27, 2007, with Randall T. Shepard, [[Chief Justice]] of the [[Indiana Supreme Court]], among the speakers.\n\n==Genealogy==\nThe Fred J. Reynolds Historical Genealogy Department, located in the Main Library Branch, is the largest public [[genealogy]] department in North America, home to more than 350,000 printed volumes and 513,000 items of [[microfilm]] and [[microfiche]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Nick | last=West | date=2009-10-09 | url=http://www.news-sentinel.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20091002/NEWS/910020346 | title=Genealogy gathering; 420 expected for conference, library's largest yet | work=[[The News-Sentinel]] | accessdate=2010-08-09 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002083952/http://www.news-sentinel.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20091002%2FNEWS%2F910020346 | archive-date=October 2, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/genealogy/index.html |publisher=Allen County Public Library |title=Genealogy Center |accessdate=2010-08-09 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808214830/http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/genealogy/index.html |archivedate=August 8, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> Only the [[Family History Library]] in [[Salt Lake City]], a private institution, is larger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lds.org/placestovisit/location/0,10634,1869-1-1-1,00.html |publisher=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints |title=Family History Library |accessdate=2010-08-09 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809124023/http://www.lds.org/placestovisit/location/0%2C10634%2C1869-1-1-1%2C00.html |archivedate=August 9, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Allen County Public Library is also a partner of [[Werelate.org|WeRelate]], a collaborative online genealogy database currently providing access to over one million records and two million person pages. The website also provides the largest documented place wiki available.\n\n==Branches==\nTen of the Allen County Public Library's branches are located within Fort Wayne. Four branches are located in municipalities within Allen County (the name of the communities these four branches are located in is indicated next to each library's name).\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break|width=20%}}\n* Aboite Branch\n* Dupont Branch\n* Georgetown Branch\n* Grabill Branch ([[Grabill, Indiana|Grabill]])\n* Hessen Cassel Branch\n* Little Turtle Branch\n* Main Branch\n{{col-break|width=65%}}\n* Monroeville Branch ([[Monroeville, Indiana|Monroeville]])\n* New Haven Branch ([[New Haven, Indiana|New Haven]])\n* Pontiac Branch\n* Shawnee Branch\n* Tecumseh Branch\n* Waynedale Branch\n* Woodburn Branch ([[Woodburn, Indiana|Woodburn]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Facilities==\nThe Main Library has five public meeting rooms that accommodate from six to 500 people. These rooms are available for use by the community for meetings and events. In addition, the building has six small group study rooms, a computer training room, and a theater which seats 230. Library branches also have meeting rooms and study rooms. The Main Library and the Georgetown branch have Maker Labs.\n\n===Access Fort Wayne===\nAccess Fort Wayne (AFW) is a [[Public-access television]] cable TV station which provides a variety of unique services for the library. AFW originates three Public-access television channels from the Main Library. Access 1 is channel 25 on [[Verizon]] and 55 on [[Comcast]]. Access 2 is channel 27 on Verizon and 57 on Comcast. [[Government-access television]] (GATV), City TV is channel 28 on Verizon and 58 on Comcast. The channels can only be viewed on Comcast and Verizon inside of Allen County. AFW is a full production facility with two TV studios and editing facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/afw/index.html |title=Allen County Public Library: Access Fort Wayne |publisher=Acpl.lib.in.us |date= |accessdate=2011-12-02}}</ref>\n\n===Audio Reading Service===\nFounded in 1979 as the Northeast Indiana Radio Reading Service (NEIRRS), the Audio Reading Service is a [[radio reading service]] for people who have visual, physical, learning, or language challenges to reading normal printed materials because of blindness, low-vision, a literacy issue, language barrier, or a physical condition. The service is for people with macular degeneration, diabetic retinopathy, arthritis, stroke, Parkinson's disease, and other conditions that affect reading traditional print. Under the leadership of library staff, volunteers read local news, grocery ads, cultural events, obituaries and other features from area newspapers, plus nearly 80 magazines and other publications. \n\nPreviously transmitted on an [[Subsidiary_communications_authority|SCA broadcast]], the Audio Reading Service can be heard on the [[HD Radio]] station 89.1 FM HD3, broadcast from Fort Wayne. HD Radios are loaned out at no cost by the library. In addition, the service is available via podcast, live web streaming, the Sero mobile app, and [[TuneIn]]; as a secondary audio program (SAP-French) on [[WFWA|PBS 39.4]]; and system-wide at select area healthcare facilities.<ref>https://acpl-cms.wise.oclc.org/explore/ars</ref>\n\nThe Audio Reading Service broadcasts 24 hours a day, seven days a week, and reaches an estimated 80,000 individuals. It became a part of the Allen County Public Library in 2004 and changed its name to Audio Reading Service in 2015. It is a member of the International Association of Audio Information Services (IAAIS).\n\n===WELT 95.7 FM===\nWELT-LP is a non-commercial radio station, produced and delivered by members of the Fort Wayne community. From the studios at the downtown branch of the Allen County Public Library, WELT-LP's volunteers and staff promote programs with news about politics and community issues, plus music and entertainment performed by local, regional and national artists in Fort Wayne venues.<ref>http://www.acpl.lib.in.us/home/using-the-library/start-here/access-fort-wayne/95-7-welt</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.acpl.info Allen County Public Library]\n* [http://www.genealogycenter.info The Genealogy Center of the Allen County Public Library]\n* [https://wiki.familysearch.org/en/Allen_County_Public_Library Allen County Public Library] at FamilySearch Research Wiki for genealogists\n\n{{Fort Wayne, Indiana}}\n\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1895]]\n[[Category:Education in Allen County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1904]]\n[[Category:Carnegie libraries in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Genealogical libraries]]\n[[Category:Education in Fort Wayne, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Fort Wayne, Indiana]]\n[[Category:1895 establishments in Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_County_Public_Library"}
{"title_page": "Austrarchaea alani", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| taxon = Austrarchaea alani\n| authority = [[Michael Gordon Rix|Rix]] & [[Mark Harvey|Harvey]], 2011\n}}\n\n'''''Austrarchaea alani''''' is a species of spider in the family Archaeidae. It is endemic to Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wsc.nmbe.ch/genus/428|title=NMBE - World Spider Catalog|website=wsc.nmbe.ch|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{Archaeidae-stub}}\n[[Category:Spiders described in 2011]]\n[[Category:Archaeidae]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| taxon = Austrarchaea alani\n| authority = [[Michael Gordon Rix|Rix]] & [[Mark Harvey|Harvey]], 2011\n}}\n\nAustrarchaea alani is a species of spider in the family Archaeidae. It is endemic to Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wsc.nmbe.ch/genus/428|title=NMBE - World Spider Catalog|website=wsc.nmbe.ch|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{Archaeidae-stub}}\n[[Category:Spiders described in 2011]]\n[[Category:Archaeidae]]\n", "name_user": "TheLordOfWikis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austrarchaea_alani"}
{"title_page": "Ahlul Bayt Digital Islamic Library Project", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=December 2017}}\n{{Primary sources|date=December 2017}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Ahlul Bayt Digital Library Project (Ahlul Bayt DILP)''', established in 1996, is a non-profit Islamic organization that features work from a group of volunteers operating throughout the world. It operates the website Al-Islam.org, whose primary objective is to digitize and present quality resources related to history, law, and society of the Islamic religion and its personalities, with particular emphasis on the Twelver Shi'ah Islamic school of thought. Al-Islam.org is a site which also serves as a means of introducing Islam to non-Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://chnm.gmu.edu/worldhistorysources/r/93/whm.html |title= The Ahlul-Bayt Digital Islamic Library Project |publisher= [[George Mason University]] |author= Sumaiya Hamdani |date= March 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Aims==\nThe Ahlul Bayt DILP's aim is to encourage the research of Islam, and to facilitate propagation of knowledge to locations where such resources are not commonly or easily accessible. To cater to this objective, the Ahlul Bayt DILP is constantly expanding its digital library, which consists of over 4000 resources accessible for free.<ref name=\"guidestar\">{{cite web |url= http://www.guidestar.org/pqShowGsReport.do?partner=justgive&ein=41-1971730 |title= Ahlul bayt digital islamic library project |publisher= JustGive.org}}</ref> The Ahlul Bayt DILP states that it also aims:\n\n{{quote|text=...to encourage research and enquiry which the use of technology facilitates. With Al-Islam.org, we attempt to present a balanced and accurate picture of Islam as it has been taught and practiced by the Most Noble Messenger Muhammad (s) and his family, the Ahlul Bayt (a). All reasonable attempts have been made to prevent inauthentic information from being carried on this site. However, we in no way can guarantee the absolute authenticity of all of the data and should not be held responsible for any errors herein. Furthermore, we do not necessarily endorse all external links from this site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-islam.org/about-us|title=About Us|website=Al-Islam.org}}</ref>}}\n\n==History==\nSince its launch, Al-islam.org has proven to be one of the most authentic sources of Shi'a Islam information, and is notable for being the top site in Yahoo!'s list of Shia sites by popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dir.yahoo.com/Society_and_Culture/Religion_and_Spirituality/Faiths_and_Practices/Islam/Sects/Shia_ism/ |title=Islamic Sects > Shia'ism |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061207190003/http://dir.yahoo.com/Society_and_Culture/Religion_and_Spirituality/Faiths_and_Practices/Islam/Sects/Shia_ism/ |archivedate=2006-12-07 }}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe organization is a 501(c)(3) public charity,<ref name=\"guidestar\"/> and is made up of volunteers who contribute articles and/or digitized materials. The DILP and the Al-Islam.org site are supported by individual donors and well-wishers.\n\n==Ongoing projects==\nOn-route to achieve a vast library with the best resource of Islamic knowledge, the Ahlul Bayt DILP team is currently working on various important projects.\n\n===Digital library===\nThe free digital library consists of more than 800 resources in different languages. To further accommodate its users, the Ahlul Bayt DILP team has been working on various projects which give detailed information on a specific topic. Such projects include the Shiite Encyclopedia, the Event of Gadeer Khum project, and Tahrif (distortion) of Islamic texts.\n\nWhile the majority of the texts currently available in the library are English translations, the DILP volunteers have taken up the task of providing texts in other languages like Spanish, Italian, Swahili, Arabic, Urdu and Gujarati.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-islam.org/alpha.php |title=Al-islam.org Free Library |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103033122/http://al-islam.org/alpha.php |archivedate=2007-01-03 }}</ref>\n\nThe digital library also includes full texts of Islamic books, written by both scholars and laymen. While it does not hold the actual copyrights on these digitized texts, permission from the copyright holders was taken in order to allow DILP and its volunteers to rectify material in terms of spelling, grammar, etc.\n\n==== Sections of the digital library ====\nThe digital library is divided into different sections, which include:\n* Belief & Creed\n* Education & Society\n* Quran & Hadith\n* History & Politics\n* Spirituality & Philosophy\n* Laws & Worship\n\n===Multimedia gallery===\nThe multimedia section of Al-islam.org has a large collection of audio/video resources. These are mainly Quran recitations, lectures, elegies, and supplications. It also has a picture gallery consisting of images of Islamic calligraphy and many important Islamic sites.\n\n===The Multilingual Quran===\nThe Multilingual Quran section of the DILP is a searchable Quran with English translation as well as commentary from Agha Puya/S.V. Mir Ahmed Ali.  It also includes multiple translations, and browsing by root-words and topics.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.al-islam.org/action.php?sid=932607912&url=%2Fquran%2F&action=go&id=29 |title= Multilingual Qur'an Project}}</ref>\n\n===Journal archives===\nThis contains archived articles from scholarly journals such as ''Al-Seerat'', ''Al-Tawheed'', and ''Al-Thaqalayn''.\n\n===The Event of Ghadir Khum project===\nThis is a scholarly examination of the event where the Prophet Muhammad appointed Imam Ali as his successor. The study focuses on examining the chain of narrators and the tradition of Al-Ghadir.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.al-islam.org/action.php?sid=932607912&url=%2Fghadir&action=go&id=35 |title= Event of Ghadir Khumm}}</ref>\n\n===Islam in a Nutshell===\nThis is a set of fact sheets, ready for distribution, which are available in numerous languages including Albanian, Bosnian, German, Swedish, and Thai.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.al-islam.org/action.php?sid=932607912&url=%2Fnutshell&action=go&id=38 |title= In a Nutshell (Factsheets in Many Languages) }}</ref>\n\n===Alif-Bot===\nThis is an informative Islamic robot which can give basic information about Islam.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.al-islam.org/action.php?sid=932607912&url=%2Falifbot%2F&action=go&id=108 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20120717195957/http://www.al-islam.org/action.php?sid=932607912&url=/alifbot/&action=go&id=108 |url-status= dead |archive-date= 2012-07-17 |title= AlifBot, The Muslim Robot }}</ref>\n\n===Islam Supplication Browser===\nThis is a multilingual collection of Ad\u2019iya and Ziaraat, categorized by source and date.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.al-islam.org/action.php?sid=932607912&url=%2Fsupplications%2F&action=go&id=15208 |title= Islamic Supplication Browser }}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n{{Prose|section|date=December 2017}}\nContent of the library has been cited by many universities and academic institutions as a source for Islamic studies, such as the\n* [[George Mason University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chnm.gmu.edu/worldhistorysources/r/93/whm.html |title=Ahlul-Bayt Digital Islamic Library Project |publisher=Chnm.gmu.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> \n* [[University of Cambridge]]<ref>http://www.divinity.cam.ac.uk/library/electronic-resources/e-books  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111101228/http://www.divinity.cam.ac.uk/library/electronic-resources/e-books |date=January 11, 2012 }}</ref> \n* [[University of California, Los Angeles|University of California Los Angeles]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://guides.library.ucla.edu/content.php?pid=22907&sid=275993 |title=Islam - Middle Eastern Studies - Research Guides at UCLA Library |publisher=Guides.library.ucla.edu |date=2013-12-09 |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> \n* [[Columbia University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.columbia.edu/indiv/area/cuvl/middle_east_studies/religion/islam.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120710224835/http://library.columbia.edu/indiv/area/cuvl/middle_east_studies/religion/islam.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 10, 2012 |accessdate=February 25, 2012 }}</ref> [[Australian National University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coombs.anu.edu.au/WWWVLPages/WhatsNewWWW/old-asian-news/archival/asia-www-monitor-02-07b.html |title=Asian Studies WWW Monitor |publisher=Coombs.anu.edu.au |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://coombs.anu.edu.au/WWWVLPages/WhatsNewWWW/old-asian-news/archival/asia-www-monitor-10-03.html |title=Asian Studies WWW Monitor - ANU College of Asia and the Pacific - ANU |publisher=Coombs.anu.edu.au |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> \n* [[New York University]]<ref>http://www.nyu.edu/gsas/program/neareast/test/8_me_resources.html</ref> \n* [[Duke University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.duke.edu/web/muslimnets/csmn_lnks.html |title=Duke University > Center for the Study of Muslim Networks > Links |publisher=Duke.edu |date=2003-04-02 |accessdate=2013-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805115356/http://www.duke.edu/web/muslimnets/csmn_lnks.html |archivedate=2011-08-05 }}</ref> \n* [[Franklin & Marshall College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.fandm.edu/guides/his373.php |title=Franklin & Marshall College Library: Research Resources: Class Guides |publisher=Library.fandm.edu |date=2001-09-11 |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref>\n* [[University of Michigan]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guides.lib.umich.edu/content.php?pid=18162&sid=223967 |title=Electronic Text Collections - Near Eastern Studies Library Resources - Research & Technology Guides at University of Michigan Library |publisher=Guides.lib.umich.edu |date=2013-12-10 |accessdate=2013-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101130055/http://guides.lib.umich.edu/content.php?pid=18162&sid=223967 |archivedate=2014-01-01 }}</ref>\n* [[State University of New York at Albany|State University of New York]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albany.edu/jmmh/vol1no1/teach-islamic.html |title=jmmh |publisher=Albany.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref>\n* [[University of Sheffield]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paths.sheffield.ac.uk/wikiana/wiki/List_of_digital_library_projects|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120713062648/http://paths.sheffield.ac.uk/wikiana/wiki/List_of_digital_library_projects|url-status=dead|title=List of digital library projects - Wikiana|date=13 July 2012|archivedate=13 July 2012}}</ref> \n* [[University of Haifa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lib.haifa.ac.il/colldev/mideast/eng/mideast_isl.html |title=Middle East |publisher=Lib.haifa.ac.il |date=2007-01-14 |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> \n* [[Utrecht University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uu.nl/university/library/en/disciplines/humanities/arabic/Pages/internetbronnen.aspx?refer=/university/library/EN/disciplines/humanities/arabic/internetbronnen |title=Internetbronnen - Library - Utrecht University |publisher=Uu.nl |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111219045514/http://www.paideiacentre.ca/ Paideia Centre for Public Theology]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paideiacentre.ca/story/theology-resources-online |accessdate=February 25, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233209/http://paideiacentre.ca/story/theology-resources-online |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref> \n* [[University of Chicago]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://teachmiddleeast.lib.uchicago.edu/historical-perspectives/the-question-of-identity/islamic-period-diversity/learning-resources/online-resources.html |title=The Question of Identity: Islamic Period: Diversity and Pluralism, Orit Bashkin |publisher=Teachmiddleeast.lib.uchicago.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> \n* [[Western Kentucky University]]<ref>http://libguides.wku.edu/content.php?pid=191211&sid=1691017 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226170924/http://libguides.wku.edu/content.php?pid=191211 |date=2012-02-26 }}</ref> \n* [http://www.mideastinfo.com/about/index.htm The Middle East Information Network]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mideastinfo.com/Religion/islam.htm |accessdate=December 30, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061222061948/http://www.mideastinfo.com/Religion/islam.htm |archivedate=December 22, 2006 }}</ref> \n* [[Middle East Policy Council]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acc.teachmideast.org/links.php?module_id=2 |title=NITLE Arab World Project |publisher=Acc.teachmideast.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> \n* [[Grand Valley State University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://libguides.gvsu.edu/content.php?pid=2673&sid=43979 |title=Recommended Websites - Middle East Studies - Subject Guides at Grand Valley State University |publisher=Libguides.gvsu.edu |date=2013-12-03 |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> \n* [[University of Melbourne]]<ref>http://cils.law.unimelb.edu.au/index.cfm?objectID=294D8923-5056-B405-51596AEC35365365&Level2=31</ref> \n* [[Vanderbilt University]]<ref>http://libstaff.library.vanderbilt.edu/Divinity/reference/ref_web_sites.htm</ref> \n* [[Saint Anselm College]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.anselm.edu/Library/Research-Help/Course-Guides/PH467Spoerl09.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-02-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922230308/http://anselm.edu/Library/Research-Help/Course-Guides/PH467Spoerl09.htm |archive-date=2010-09-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n* [http://www.humanitarian.net/ Humanitarian Resource Institute]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanitarian.net/interfaith/studycenter/|title=Interfaith News Network|first=SMAMedia|last=Communications|website=www.humanitarian.net}}</ref> \n* [[University of St. Michael's College]]<ref>http://stmikes.utoronto.ca/kelly/research_guides/pdf/islam.pdf{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=Interne