l/worldrel.html |archivedate=2004-10-16 }}</ref> \n* [[Ohio University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://infotree.library.ohiou.edu/single-records/3460.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417221111/http://infotree.library.ohiou.edu/single-records/3460.html |archivedate=2012-04-17 }}</ref> \n* [[Drexel University]]<ref>http://dlib.ischool.drexel.edu/drupal/?q=category/organization/non-profit/ahlul-bayt-digital-islamic-library-project</ref> \n* [[Ghent University]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.flw.ugent.be/cie/CIE_links_frame.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-02-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101001146/http://www.flw.ugent.be/cie/CIE_links_frame.htm |archive-date=2012-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n* [[Library of Congress]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lcweb4.loc.gov/911/911/DrillSearch?x=d&t=Public+Interest/Advocacy&dp=.t|title=About this Collection \u00a0-\u00a0September 11, 2001 Web Archive \u00a0-\u00a0Digital Collections \u00a0-\u00a0Library of Congress|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lcweb4.loc.gov/911/catalog/2507.html|title=About this Collection \u00a0-\u00a0September 11, 2001 Web Archive \u00a0-\u00a0Digital Collections \u00a0-\u00a0Library of Congress|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Aalulbayt (a.s.) Global Information Center]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |url= http://www.al-islam.org/  |title= Al-Islam.org by the Ahlul Bayt DILP - Home }}\n*[http://lcweb4.loc.gov/911/catalog/2507.html archived] and part of the [[Minerva (disambiguation)|Minerva]] project of the [[Library of Congress]]\n*[[MENALIB|Middle East Virtual Library]] https://web.archive.org/web/20070703054220/http://ssgdoc.bibliothek.uni-halle.de/vlib/ssgfi/infodata/000520.html\n\n[[Category:Shia organizations]]\n[[Category:Islamic libraries]]\n[[Category:American digital libraries]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ahlul_Bayt_Digital_Islamic_Library_Project"}
{"title_page": "Academica (library)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Academica (disambiguation){{!}}Academica}}\n'''Academica''' is a  Polish online interlibrary system providing access to digital documents of the [[National Library of Poland]] that includes both copyrighted material for registered users in selected libraries within Poland as well as free access to public domain material.\n\nIts scope is similar to that of the [[Cyfrowa Biblioteka Narodowa Polona|Digital Library of National Library of Poland]] and allows access to digitized periodicals, books, scores, and other library material within broad range of sciences and humanities. The project was developed in collaboration with the [[National Library of Poland]], [[Foundation for Polish Science]] and [[Naukowa i Akademicka Sie\u0107 Komputerowa|Research and Academic Computer Network]].<ref>{{Cite news | last =| first=| title = Ruszy\u0142 system Academica - Biblioteka Narodowa otworzy\u0142a swoje magazyny| url =http://wyborcza.pl/1,91446,17155306,Ruszyl_system_Academica___Biblioteka_Narodowa_otworzyla.html | newspaper = Gazeta Wyborcza |publication-date = 18 December 2014| language = pl}}{{dead link|date=September 2017}}</ref> The system is available since 2014. As of September 2017 ''Academica'' catalog lists 2,020,299 documents. The interface allows for search within the digitized version of the documents as well as its metadata including language, keywords, published date, and subject categories. It provides capability to perform full text searches for materials with [[optical character recognition|OCR]] and limited capability for boolean expressions (for example it is possible to do fulltext search for \"Jan Kowalski\").<!-- Not a boolean expression -->\n\nAdditional functionality changes such as additional search options, increased OCR capabilities and access improvements are planned for 2017\u20132019 within the project OMNIS<ref>[http://www.bn.org.pl/omnis/o-projekcie/ Project e-us\u0142uga OMNIS]</ref> supported mostly by [[European Union]] funds.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://academica.edu.pl/}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:National libraries]]\n[[Category:Polish digital libraries]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Academica (disambiguation){{!}}Academica}}\n'''Academica''' is a  Polish online interlibrary system providing access to digital documents of the [[National Library of Poland]] that includes both copyrighted material for registered users in selected libraries within Poland as well as free access to public domain material.\n\nIts scope is similar to that of the [[Cyfrowa Biblioteka Narodowa Polona|Digital Library of National Library of Poland]] and allows access to digitized periodicals, books, scores, and other library material within broad range of sciences and humanities. The project was developed in collaboration with the [[National Library of Poland]], [[Foundation for Polish Science]] and [[Naukowa i Akademicka Sie\u0107 Komputerowa|Research and Academic Computer Network]].<ref>{{Cite news | last =| first=| title = Ruszy\u0142 system Academica - Biblioteka Narodowa otworzy\u0142a swoje magazyny| url =http://wyborcza.pl/1,91446,17155306,Ruszyl_system_Academica___Biblioteka_Narodowa_otworzyla.html | newspaper = Gazeta Wyborcza |publication-date = 18 December 2014| language = pl}}{{dead link|date=September 2017}}</ref> The system is available since 2014. As of September 2017 ''Academica'' catalog lists 2,020,299 documents. The interface allows for search within the digitized version of the documents as well as its metadata including language, keywords, published date, and subject categories. It provides capability to perform full text searches for materials with [[optical character recognition|OCR]] and limited capability for boolean expressions (for example it is possible to do fulltext search for \"Jan Kowalski\").<!-- Not a boolean expression -->\n\nAdditional functionality changes such as additional search options, increased OCR capabilities and access improvements are planned for 2017\u20132019 within the project OMNIS<ref>[http://www.bn.org.pl/omnis/o-projekcie/ Project e-us\u0142uga OMNIS]</ref> supported mostly by [[European Union]] funds.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://academica.edu.pl/}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:National libraries]]\n[[Category:Polish digital libraries]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academica_(library)"}
{"title_page": "Samantha Eggar", "text_new": "{{short description|English actress}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Samantha Eggar.jpg\n| caption      = Samantha Eggar in a publicity photo in 1964\n| name         = Samantha Eggar\n| birth_name   = Victoria Louise Samantha Marie Elizabeth Therese Eggar\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1939|3|5}}\n| birth_place  = [[Hampstead]], [[London]], England\n| occupation   = Actress\n| residence    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| citizenship  = British; American\n| years_active = 1960\u20132012\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Tom Stern|end=div.|1964|1971}}\n| children     = [[Nicolas Stern]]<br>[[Jenna Stern]]\n}}\n'''Victoria Louise Samantha Marie Elizabeth Therese Eggar''' (born 5 March 1939) is a British-American film, stage, television, and voice actress. After beginning her career in Shakespearean theatre, she rose to fame for her performance in [[William Wyler]]'s thriller ''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]'' (1965), which earned her a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Motion Picture \u2013 Drama|Golden Globe Award]] and an [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy Award]] nomination for Best Actress.\n\nShe later appeared as Emma Fairfax in ''[[Doctor Dolittle (film)|Doctor Dolittle]]'' (1967), and the American drama ''[[The Molly Maguires (film)|The Molly Maguires]]'' (1970). In the early 1970s, Eggar relocated to the United States and Canada, where she later starred in several horror films, including ''[[The Dead Are Alive]]'' (1972), ''[[The Uncanny (film)|The Uncanny]]'' (1977), and [[David Cronenberg]]'s [[cult film|cult]] thriller ''[[The Brood]]'' (1979).\n\nEggar has also worked as a voice actress, as [[Hera]] in [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney]]'s ''[[Hercules (1997 film)|Hercules]]'' (1997), and lent her voice to several video games, including ''[[Gabriel Knight 3: Blood of the Sacred, Blood of the Damned]]'' and ''[[007: Nightfire]]''. Her television work includes roles on ''[[Fantasy Island]]'', and a recurring part as Charlotte Devane in the soap opera ''[[All My Children]]'' in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/samantha-eggar-16730280|publisher=Biography.com|title=Samantha Eggar Biography|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSamantha Eggar was born '''Victoria Louise Samantha Marie Elizabeth Therese Eggar'''{{Sfn|Cooper|2015|p=105}}<ref name=gg>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com/show/81/Samantha+Eggar/index.html|work=Glamour Girls of the Silver Screen|accessdate=22 January 2017|title=The Private Life and Times of Samantha Eggar}}</ref> on 5 March 1939<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b9efa8114|publisher=The British Film Institute|title=Samantha Eggar|accessdate=29 December 2016}}</ref> in [[Hampstead]], London, to Ralph Alfred James (a [[brigadier]] in the British Army) and a mother (Muriel Olga Palache-Bouma) of Dutch and Portuguese descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/21328/Samantha-Eggar|work=The New York Times|title=Samantha Eggar Biography|archivedate=18 January 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118120414/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/21328/Samantha-Eggar|accessdate=22 December 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/eggar-samantha-1939|title=Contemporary Theatre, Film, and Television|last=|first=|publisher=Gale Research Company|year=2004|isbn=978-0787670986|location=|pages=|chapter=Eggar, Samantha 1939\u2013|via=Encyclopedia.com}}</ref> Soon after her birth her family relocated to rural [[Bledlow]], [[Buckinghamshire]], during World War II, where she spent her childhood.{{Sfn|Cooper|2015|p=105}}\n\nEggar was brought up as a Catholic and educated at St Mary's Providence Convent in [[Woking]], Surrey. Reflecting on her time in convent school, Eggar said: \"The nuns didn't have too much success with me&nbsp;\u2013 I've always had a violent temper. In fact, once I almost killed one of the nuns.\"<ref name=gg/> At age 16, she began to go by the name Samantha.{{Sfn|Cooper|2015|p=105}} Although Eggar expressed interest in acting at a young age, she was urged against a career in the theatre by her parents. She was offered a scholarship to the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts]], but instead studied fashion for two years at the Thanet School of Art.<ref name=gg/> After completing her studies, she enrolled at the [[Webber Douglas Academy of Dramatic Art]] in London.{{Sfn|Cooper|2015|p=106}}\n\n==Career==\n===Theatre and early work===\nEggar began her acting career in several [[William Shakespeare|Shakespearean]] companies, notably playing [[Titania]] in a 1962 production of ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'', directed by [[Tony Richardson]].{{Sfn|Cooper|2015|p=120}} She also appeared onstage in a production of [[Douglas Seale]]'s ''Landscape with Figures'', where she was noticed by a talent scout, and from there was cast in the biographical film ''[[Dr. Crippen (1962 film)|Dr. Crippen]]'' (1962), opposite [[Donald Pleasence]].{{Sfn|Cooper|2015|p=107}} Her second film role was in 1962 in ''[[The Wild and the Willing]]''; the same year, she appeared onstage again as [[Olivia (Twelfth Night)|Olivia]] in a production of ''[[Twelfth Night]]'' by [[George Devine]].{{Sfn|Cooper|2015|p=120}}\n\nIn 1965, Eggar appeared in the thriller ''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]'', directed by [[William Wyler]], playing a kidnap victim. She received a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]], and won a [[Golden Globe]] award for her performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/person/samantha-eggar|publisher=GoldenGlobes.com|title=Samantha Eggar|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref> She was also awarded [[Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation f\u00e9minine|Best Actress]] at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Awards|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/archives/1965/allAward.html|work=Awards 1965|publisher=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> On her role as Miranda in ''The Collector'', Eggar has said: \"My biggest relationship on set was with William Wyler. The tension on set was real. And if the tension wasn't there&nbsp;\u2013 if I didn't exude precisely what he wanted&nbsp;\u2013 well, Willie just poured cold water over me.\"<ref name=tt>{{cite web|url=http://www.terrortrap.com/interviews/samanthaeggar/|title=Collecting Life: An Interview with Samantha Eggar|date=July 2014|work=The Terror Trap|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, Eggar starred in the comedy ''[[Walk, Don't Run]]'' (1966) with [[Cary Grant]] (his last [[motion picture]]) and [[Jim Hutton]], followed by a lead role as Emma Fairfax in [[Richard Fleischer]]'s musical adaptation of ''[[Doctor Dolittle (film)|Doctor Dolittle]]'' (1967). In 1963, she played the title character in \"Marcia\", a second-season episode of ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]''. After her appearance in ''The Saint'', Eggar did not appear in television for 10 years, instead focusing exclusively on feature films. These included ''[[The Molly Maguires (film)|The Molly Maguires]]'' (1970), in which she starred with [[Sean Connery]], and ''[[The Light at the Edge of the World]]'' (1971), in which she starred with [[Kirk Douglas]]. Although she co-starred with [[Yul Brynner]] in the television series ''[[Anna and the King (TV series)|Anna and the King]]'' (1972), she did not make another television guest appearance until 1973, when she starred in the episode \"The Cardboard House\" of the romantic anthology series ''[[Love Story (1973 TV series)|Love Story]]''. That same year, she played [[Phyllis Dietrichson]] in a TV remake of ''[[Double Indemnity (film)|Double Indemnity]]''.{{Sfn|MacKellar|2006|p=371}}\n\n===Move to United States and Canada===\nIn 1973, Eggar relocated to the United States, settling in Los Angeles, and appeared first in television, guest starring on episodes of ''[[Starsky & Hutch]]'' and ''[[Columbo]]'', the latter with [[Peter Falk]] and [[Theodore Bikel]] in the episode \"The Bye-Bye Sky High IQ Murder Case\". She would go on to star in a number of horror films, including ''[[The Dead Are Alive]]'' (1972), ''[[A Name for Evil]]'' (1973), ''[[The Uncanny (film)|The Uncanny]]'' (1977), and [[David Cronenberg]]'s [[cult film|cult]] sci-fi film ''[[The Brood]]'' (1979). In 1980, she filmed the Canadian slasher film ''[[Curtains (1983 film)|Curtains]]'', released in 1983.{{Sfn|Nowell|2010|p=232}}\n\nShe also appeared as Maggie Gioberti in \"The Vintage Years\", the pilot for the drama ''[[Falcon Crest]]'', but was replaced by [[Susan Sullivan]] when the series went into production.<ref name=gg/> She appeared in the drama ''[[Dark Horse (1992 film)|Dark Horse]]'' (1992), followed by the superhero film ''[[The Phantom (1996 film)|The Phantom]]'' (1996). In 1997, she provided the voice of [[Hera]] in Disney's animated film ''[[Hercules (1997 film)|Hercules]]''; she would also supply the voice for the subsequent television series. Eggar also had a role in the sci-fi thriller ''[[The Astronaut's Wife]]'' (1999), which starred [[Johnny Depp]].\n\nShe has appeared as the wife of Captain [[Jean-Luc Picard]]'s brother Robert on the television series ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', and as Sarah Templeton, the wife of [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] Nathan Templeton ([[Donald Sutherland]]), on the short-lived television series ''[[Commander in Chief (TV series)|Commander in Chief]]'', which starred [[Geena Davis]]. In the year 2000, she had a brief run as Charlotte Devane in the American soap opera ''[[All My Children]]''. In 2003, she appeared in the first season of ''[[Cold Case]]'', episode 14 (\"The Boy in the Box\") as Sister Vivian. In 2009, she played the mother of Jack and Becky Gallagher in season 1, episode 11 (\"Lines in the Sand\") of the Fox television series ''[[Mental (TV series)|Mental]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1964, she married actor Tom Stern, and the couple have two children: film producer [[Nicolas Stern]] (b. 1965),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/nicolas_stern_born_1965_9365350|work=California Birth Index|title=Nicolas Stern was born on September 12, 1965 in Los Angeles County, California|accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref> and actress [[Jenna Stern]] (b. 1967).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/jenna_l_stern_born_1967_10052098|work=California Birth Index|title=Jenna L Stern was born on September 23, 1967 in Los Angeles County, California|accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref> Eggar and Stern divorced in 1971.\n\nEggar holds dual UK and American citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.samanthaeggar.net|work=Samantha Eggar: Official Website|title=Samantha Celebrates Queen Elizabeth's Diamond Jubilee|date=April 2012|quote=I am now an American citizen, but my heritage is indomitable.|accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref> She resides in Los Angeles.<ref name=tt/>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Roles\n! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1962\n|''[[Dr. Crippen (1962 film)|Dr. Crippen]]''\n|[[Ethel Le Neve]] \n|\n|-\n|''[[The Wild and the Willing]]''\n|Josie \n|\n|-\n|1963\n|''[[Doctor in Distress (film)|Doctor in Distress]]''\n|Delia Mallory \n|\n|-\n|1964\n|''[[Psyche 59]]''\n|Robin \n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1965\n|''[[Return from the Ashes]]''\n|Fabienne 'Fabi' Wolf\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Collector (1965 film)|The Collector]]''\n|Miranda Grey\n|Also known as ''The Butterfly Collector''<br>[[Best Actress Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Cannes Film Festival Best Actress Award]]<br>[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama]]<br>[[Sant Jordi Award]] for Best Performance in a Foreign Film<br>Nominated